digraph G {
    graph [
        rankdir=TB,
        splines=ortho,
        overlap=false,
        concentrate=true,
        nodesep=0.7,
        ranksep=1.1,
        pad=0.2
    ];
    node [
        shape=box,
        style="rounded,filled",
        color="gray40",
        fontname="Helvetica"
    ];
    edge [
        color="gray55",
        penwidth=1.2,
        arrowsize=0.8
    ];
    "29033327.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">29033327.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Formulation of the Multiple Premise Entailment<BR/>(MPE) task</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Natural Language Inference from Multiple Premises</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper defines a new textual entailment task,<BR/>Multiple Premise Entailment (MPE), in which each<BR/>example consists of an unordered set of four<BR/>independently written image captions (premises)<BR/>and a single hypothesis sentence. The hypothesis<BR/>must be classified as entailment, neutral, or<BR/>contradiction with respect to the combined<BR/>information from all premises. This formulation<BR/>extends standard single‑premise natural language<BR/>inference by requiring aggregation across multiple<BR/>sentences, handling cross‑sentence coreference and<BR/>event resolution, and by deliberately limiting<BR/>lexical overlap between premises and hypothesis.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#fde0c5"];
    "14604520.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">14604520.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Stanford Natural Language Inference (SNLI) Corpus</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">A large annotated corpus for learning natural<BR/>language inference</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces SNLI, a freely available<BR/>collection of 570,152 human‑written sentence pairs<BR/>labeled for entailment, contradiction, and neutral<BR/>(semantic independence). The pairs are generated<BR/>by crowdsourcing hypotheses for image captions<BR/>drawn from the Flickr30k corpus, with a balanced<BR/>three‑class distribution and a validation phase<BR/>involving multiple annotators to ensure high<BR/>quality. SNLI includes predefined train/dev/test<BR/>splits, constituency parses produced by the<BR/>Stanford PCFG parser, and is released under a<BR/>Creative Commons Attribution‑ShareAlike license,<BR/>establishing a large‑scale benchmark for<BR/>evaluating semantic representation learning and<BR/>natural language inference models.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "16404002.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">16404002.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">SICK (Sentences Involving Compositional Knowledge)<BR/>dataset</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">SemEval-2014 Task 1: Evaluation of Compositional<BR/>Distributional Semantic Models on Full Sentences<BR/>through Semantic Relatedness and Textual<BR/>Entailment</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors constructed a corpus of roughly 10,000<BR/>English sentence pairs, each annotated for (i)<BR/>semantic relatedness on a 5‑point continuous scale<BR/>and (ii) textual entailment (ENTAILMENT,<BR/>CONTRADICTION, NEUTRAL). The pairs were generated<BR/>through a controlled three‑step pipeline<BR/>(normalization, expansion, pairing) to exhibit a<BR/>wide range of lexical, syntactic and semantic<BR/>compositional phenomena (e.g., active/passive<BR/>alternations, negation, operator scope) while<BR/>deliberately avoiding reliance on encyclopedic<BR/>world knowledge. The resource is released both as<BR/>a dataset for research and as a benchmark for<BR/>evaluating compositional distributional semantic<BR/>models (CDSMs) on full‑sentence semantics.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "14604520.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">14604520.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Crowdsourced High-Quality NLI Data Collection<BR/>Protocol</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">A large annotated corpus for learning natural<BR/>language inference</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors devise a reproducible crowdsourcing<BR/>workflow on Amazon Mechanical Turk that presents<BR/>workers with image captions from the Flickr30k<BR/>corpus as premises and asks them to write three<BR/>hypotheses—one entailing, one neutral, and one<BR/>contradictory—thereby guaranteeing a balanced<BR/>three‑class distribution. The protocol includes<BR/>detailed written instructions, an evolving FAQ,<BR/>qualification filters to exclude low‑quality<BR/>workers, and a validation stage where each pair is<BR/>re‑annotated by four additional annotators,<BR/>yielding a gold label with 98 % consensus on a<BR/>held‑out subset. By grounding each pair in a<BR/>specific visual scenario, the design mitigates<BR/>event and entity coreference ambiguities and<BR/>enforces high annotation reliability.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "5555594.c3" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">5555594.c3</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Contradiction detection system with<BR/>event‑coreference filtering</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Finding Contradictions in Text</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper implements an end‑to‑end<BR/>contradiction‑detection pipeline built on the<BR/>Stanford Recognizing Textual Entailment (RTE)<BR/>system. It adds an event‑coreference filtering<BR/>stage that discards sentence pairs that do not<BR/>describe the same event, using a root‑alignment<BR/>heuristic together with an unweighted<BR/>topicality‑based scoring model. The remaining<BR/>pairs are processed by a rich feature extractor<BR/>(polarity, numeric, antonymy, structural,<BR/>factivity, modality, relational) and classified<BR/>with a logistic‑regression model, producing a tool<BR/>for fine‑grained contradiction detection.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "5555594.c5" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">5555594.c5</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Topicality‑based event‑coreference scoring method</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Finding Contradictions in Text</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces an unweighted topicality<BR/>model that assigns higher weights to noun phrases<BR/>appearing earlier in a sentence, using their<BR/>linear position derived from typed dependency<BR/>parses. A normalized topicality score is computed<BR/>for each aligned noun‑phrase pair between a text<BR/>and a hypothesis, and combined with a<BR/>root‑alignment heuristic to decide whether the two<BR/>sentences describe the same event. This filtering<BR/>step improves precision of contradiction detection<BR/>beyond using root‑alignment alone.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "207847663.c2-1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">207847663.c2-1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Hard-selection baseline models for rationalized<BR/>predictions</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">ERASER : A Benchmark to Evaluate Rationalized NLP<BR/>Models</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper implements three hard-selection<BR/>architectures that produce discrete rationales and<BR/>use only the extracted snippets for downstream<BR/>prediction. The first adapts the Lei et al. (2016)<BR/>rationalizer, training a binary mask encoder and a<BR/>classifier decoder jointly with REINFORCE, using<BR/>either BERT or GloVe embeddings as token encoders.<BR/>The second is a pipeline that first extracts<BR/>sentence-level rationales with a GRU-based encoder<BR/>and then classifies using a separate model. The<BR/>third is a BERT-to-BERT pipeline where a BERT<BR/>encoder selects rationales and a second BERT model<BR/>consumes them for prediction. All models are<BR/>trained on the ERASER benchmark datasets and<BR/>released as open-source code.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#fde0c5"];
    "7205805.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">7205805.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Modular encoder‑generator framework for<BR/>rationale‑based prediction</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Rationalizing Neural Predictions</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper proposes a high‑level conceptual<BR/>framework that separates a rationale generator,<BR/>which extracts a short, coherent subset of the<BR/>input text, from an encoder that makes task<BR/>predictions using only the selected rationale. The<BR/>generator and encoder are instantiated with<BR/>bidirectional RCNNs (the generator with<BR/>independent or recurrent selection mechanisms, the<BR/>encoder as a standard RCNN classifier). The two<BR/>modules are trained jointly with a combined<BR/>prediction loss and sparsity/continuity<BR/>regularizer, using a REINFORCE‑style doubly<BR/>stochastic gradient estimator to handle the<BR/>discrete latent rationale selections. This enables<BR/>accurate predictions together with interpretable<BR/>justifications without any rationale annotations.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "6468765.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">6468765.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Gated non-consecutive convolutional encoder (RCNN)<BR/>for question representation</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Semi-supervised Question Retrieval with Gated<BR/>Convolutions</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces a recurrent convolutional<BR/>neural network (RCNN) that extends the<BR/>non‑consecutive convolutional model of Lei et al.<BR/>(2015) with an adaptive gating mechanism. At each<BR/>time step a gate λ_t, computed from the current<BR/>token embedding and the previous hidden state,<BR/>modulates how much of the accumulated n‑gram<BR/>features are retained, allowing the model to<BR/>emphasize salient words and suppress noisy tokens<BR/>in long question bodies. The sequence of gated<BR/>hidden states is pooled (mean or last state) to<BR/>produce a fixed‑dimensional question vector, and<BR/>cosine similarity between vectors is used to rank<BR/>candidate questions for retrieval.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "11212020.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">11212020.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Soft attention mechanism for differentiable<BR/>alignment</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Neural Machine Translation by Jointly Learning to<BR/>Align and Translate</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces a soft attention mechanism<BR/>that, for each target word, computes a context<BR/>vector as a weighted sum of encoder annotations.<BR/>The attention weights \(\alpha_{ij}\) are obtained<BR/>from a feed‑forward alignment model that scores<BR/>the compatibility between the decoder hidden state<BR/>and each source annotation, and are normalised<BR/>with a softmax. Because the whole computation is<BR/>differentiable, gradients can flow through the<BR/>alignment scores, allowing the attention<BR/>parameters, encoder, and decoder to be trained<BR/>jointly, replacing the static fixed‑length context<BR/>vector of basic encoder‑decoder models.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "11212020.c3" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">11212020.c3</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Joint end‑to‑end training of attention and<BR/>translation</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Neural Machine Translation by Jointly Learning to<BR/>Align and Translate</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces a training procedure that<BR/>jointly optimises the parameters of the encoder,<BR/>decoder and the soft attention (alignment) model<BR/>by maximising the conditional likelihood of the<BR/>target sentence given the source. The attention<BR/>weights \(\alpha_{ij}\) are computed by a<BR/>feed‑forward alignment network and are<BR/>incorporated as differentiable nodes in the<BR/>computational graph, allowing gradients to flow<BR/>from the translation loss through the alignment<BR/>scores back to the encoder and decoder. This<BR/>unified objective replaces the traditional<BR/>two‑stage approach where alignment is treated as a<BR/>latent variable and learned separately.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "17195923.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">17195923.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Recurrent Attention Model (RAM) architecture</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Recurrent Models of Visual Attention</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces a novel recurrent neural<BR/>network architecture for visual processing that<BR/>sequentially selects fixation locations, extracts<BR/>a multi‑resolution retinal glimpse at each<BR/>location, and integrates these glimpses over time<BR/>with a core RNN. The hidden state of the RNN feeds<BR/>a stochastic location network that chooses the<BR/>next fixation and an action network that produces<BR/>task‑specific outputs such as classification or<BR/>control. Because computation is limited to the<BR/>glimpses, the amount of processing is independent<BR/>of the full image size while still providing<BR/>translation invariance.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "17195923.c2" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">17195923.c2</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">End-to-end training of RAM with REINFORCE, learned<BR/>baseline, and hybrid supervised loss</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Recurrent Models of Visual Attention</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces a training procedure for the<BR/>Recurrent Attention Model (RAM) that combines<BR/>standard back‑propagation for differentiable<BR/>components (glimpse, core, and action networks)<BR/>with a REINFORCE policy‑gradient update for the<BR/>stochastic location network. To reduce the high<BR/>variance of the REINFORCE estimator, a learned<BR/>baseline (value function) is trained jointly with<BR/>the model. For classification tasks the final<BR/>action output is also trained with a supervised<BR/>cross‑entropy loss, yielding a hybrid objective<BR/>that leverages both reinforcement and supervised<BR/>signals.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "52967399.c7" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">52967399.c7</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Open-source release of BERT code and pretrained<BR/>checkpoints</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">BERT: Pre-training of Deep Bidirectional<BR/>Transformers for Language Understanding</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors publicly release a TensorFlow<BR/>implementation of BERT together with the<BR/>pretrained BERT‑BASE and BERT‑LARGE model<BR/>checkpoints via a GitHub repository. The release<BR/>includes all source files needed to reproduce the<BR/>model architecture, pre‑training procedures, and<BR/>fine‑tuning scripts. By providing the code and<BR/>weights, the work enables reproducibility, rapid<BR/>prototyping, and further research by the community<BR/>without requiring re‑training from scratch.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "1957433.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">1957433.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">GloVe: Global Log‑Bilinear Regression Model for<BR/>Word Embeddings</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">GloVe: Global Vectors for Word Representation</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces GloVe, a novel word‑embedding<BR/>model that directly factorizes a global word‑word<BR/>co‑occurrence matrix using a weighted log‑bilinear<BR/>regression objective. By modeling the logarithm of<BR/>co‑occurrence counts with a weighted least‑squares<BR/>loss, the method combines the statistical<BR/>efficiency of global matrix‑factorization<BR/>approaches with the ability of local<BR/>context‑window models to capture linear<BR/>substructures such as analogies. The resulting<BR/>vectors encode semantic and syntactic regularities<BR/>and achieve state‑of‑the‑art performance on<BR/>analogy, similarity, and named‑entity‑recognition<BR/>benchmarks.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "12730203.c6" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">12730203.c6</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Explicit high‑dimensional sparse word vectors from<BR/>Wikipedia using PPMI</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Linguistic Regularities in Sparse and Explicit<BR/>Word Representations</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors build a traditional distributional<BR/>representation by counting word–context<BR/>co‑occurrences within a symmetric window of two<BR/>tokens on the English Wikipedia corpus. They<BR/>weight the raw counts with positive pointwise<BR/>mutual information (PPMI) to obtain a |V|×|C|<BR/>sparse matrix where each dimension corresponds to<BR/>a positional context (e.g., &quot;-2&quot;, &quot;+1&quot;). This<BR/>explicit vector space serves as a reproducible<BR/>baseline for relational similarity experiments and<BR/>demonstrates that large‑scale sparse vectors can<BR/>be constructed from publicly available data.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "7478738.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">7478738.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Vector offset algorithm for word analogy solving</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Linguistic Regularities in Continuous Space Word<BR/>Representations</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces a simple algorithm that<BR/>solves word analogy questions of the form &quot;a is to<BR/>b as c is to ?&quot; by computing the vector y = xb –<BR/>xa + xc, normalising the resulting vector to unit<BR/>length, and selecting the vocabulary word whose<BR/>embedding has the highest cosine similarity to y.<BR/>The method directly exploits the empirically<BR/>observed constant offset property of word<BR/>embeddings learned by a recurrent neural network<BR/>language model. It provides a fast,<BR/>language‑independent reasoning mechanism that can<BR/>be applied to both syntactic and semantic analogy<BR/>sets.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "1957433.c8" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">1957433.c8</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Open‑Source Implementation and Pre‑trained Word<BR/>Vectors Release</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">GloVe: Global Vectors for Word Representation</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors publicly release the software for<BR/>training the GloVe model together with pretrained<BR/>word‑vector embeddings learned on several large<BR/>corpora (Wikipedia 2010/2014, Gigaword 5, Common<BR/>Crawl). The code, scripts, and vector files are<BR/>hosted at http://nlp.stanford.edu/projects/glove/,<BR/>enabling reproducibility and immediate downstream<BR/>use by the research community.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "5590763.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">5590763.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Gated Recurrent Unit (reset and update gates)</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Learning Phrase Representations using RNN<BR/>Encoder–Decoder for Statistical Machine<BR/>Translation</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces a novel recurrent hidden unit<BR/>that augments the standard RNN state with two<BR/>multiplicative gates: a reset gate r that controls<BR/>how much of the previous hidden state is ignored<BR/>when computing the candidate activation, and an<BR/>update gate z that interpolates between the<BR/>previous hidden state and the candidate<BR/>activation, thereby adaptively remembering or<BR/>forgetting information. The unit’s equations<BR/>(5)–(8) are computationally simpler than the LSTM<BR/>while providing comparable adaptive memory<BR/>capabilities. This gated unit is employed in both<BR/>the encoder and decoder of the proposed RNN<BR/>Encoder–Decoder architecture.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "12485056.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">12485056.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Leaky‑integration hidden units for longer temporal<BR/>dependencies</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Advances in optimizing recurrent networks</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper augments standard recurrent neural<BR/>networks by assigning a subset of hidden units<BR/>leaky‑integration dynamics: ht,i = αi ht−1,i + (1<BR/>− αi) F_i(ht−1,xt), where αi is sampled uniformly<BR/>from (0.02, 0.2). These slower‑changing units act<BR/>as low‑pass filters, providing shorter effective<BR/>gradient paths that mitigate vanishing gradients<BR/>and allow information to persist over longer<BR/>time‑scales. Experiments on polyphonic music and<BR/>Penn Treebank language modeling demonstrate lower<BR/>training and test loss compared to vanilla RNNs.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "7365802.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">7365802.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">ADADELTA adaptive learning‑rate algorithm</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">ADADELTA: An Adaptive Learning Rate Method</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">ADADELTA is a per‑dimension adaptive learning‑rate<BR/>method that updates parameters using only<BR/>first‑order gradient information. It maintains an<BR/>exponentially decaying average of squared<BR/>gradients (RMS[g]) for the denominator and an<BR/>exponentially decaying average of past parameter<BR/>updates (RMS[Δx]) for the numerator, yielding the<BR/>unit‑consistent update Δx = - (RMS[Δx]_{t-1} /<BR/>RMS[g]_{t}) * g_t. The algorithm removes the need<BR/>for a manually tuned global learning rate, adds<BR/>only trivial overhead to vanilla SGD, and is<BR/>robust across network architectures, data<BR/>modalities, and distributed training settings.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "6628106.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">6628106.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Adam: Adaptive Moment Estimation Optimization<BR/>Algorithm</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Adam: A Method for Stochastic Optimization</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">Adam is a first‑order stochastic optimization<BR/>method that computes per‑parameter learning rates<BR/>using exponential moving averages of the gradient<BR/>(first moment) and the squared gradient (second<BR/>raw moment). The algorithm incorporates<BR/>bias‑corrected moment estimates to eliminate<BR/>initialization bias, yields updates invariant to<BR/>diagonal rescaling of gradients, and bounds the<BR/>effective step size by a global stepsize<BR/>hyper‑parameter. Designed for non‑stationary<BR/>objectives and sparse or noisy gradients, Adam<BR/>requires only minimal additional memory and<BR/>computation beyond standard stochastic gradient<BR/>descent.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "202786778.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">202786778.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Imperative define‑by‑run deep learning library<BR/>(PyTorch)</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">PyTorch: An Imperative Style, High-Performance<BR/>Deep Learning Library</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces PyTorch, a Python library<BR/>that performs immediate (eager) execution of<BR/>tensor operations while providing reverse‑mode<BR/>automatic differentiation and GPU acceleration. By<BR/>embracing Python&#x27;s imperative programming model,<BR/>models, data loaders, and optimizers can be<BR/>written as ordinary Python code, enabling<BR/>straightforward debugging and rapid<BR/>experimentation. The authors demonstrate that<BR/>careful engineering allows PyTorch to achieve<BR/>performance comparable to static‑graph frameworks,<BR/>challenging the belief that dynamic execution<BR/>necessarily incurs a large speed penalty.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "207847663.c2-2" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">207847663.c2-2</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Soft‑selection baseline models for rationalized<BR/>predictions</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">ERASER : A Benchmark to Evaluate Rationalized NLP<BR/>Models</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper implements a suite of soft‑selection<BR/>baselines that assign continuous importance scores<BR/>to each token. A BERT encoder followed by a<BR/>bidirectional LSTM produces contextual token<BR/>representations; token‑level attention,<BR/>gradient‑based saliency, and LIME are applied to<BR/>obtain soft importance scores. These scores are<BR/>evaluated for agreement with human rationales and<BR/>for faithfulness using the ERASER metrics. The<BR/>models are trained on the ERASER benchmark and the<BR/>implementation is released as open‑source code.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#fde0c5"];
    "52967399.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">52967399.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Bidirectional Transformer encoder architecture<BR/>(BERT)</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">BERT: Pre-training of Deep Bidirectional<BR/>Transformers for Language Understanding</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">BERT introduces a multi‑layer Transformer encoder<BR/>in which every token attends to both its left and<BR/>right context through fully bidirectional<BR/>self‑attention. The model combines WordPiece token<BR/>embeddings, learned segment embeddings, positional<BR/>embeddings, and special tokens ([CLS], [SEP]) to<BR/>represent single sentences or sentence pairs<BR/>uniformly. This architecture serves as a universal<BR/>language representation that can be fine‑tuned<BR/>with a minimal task‑specific output layer for a<BR/>wide range of NLP tasks.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "13756489.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">13756489.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Transformer: attention‑only encoder‑decoder<BR/>architecture</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Attention is All you Need</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper presents the Transformer, a novel<BR/>sequence‑to‑sequence model that replaces recurrent<BR/>and convolutional layers with stacks of multi‑head<BR/>self‑attention and position‑wise feed‑forward<BR/>networks in both encoder and decoder. Positional<BR/>information is injected via sinusoidal encodings,<BR/>and the model employs residual connections, layer<BR/>normalization, weight tying, dropout, label<BR/>smoothing, and a warm‑up inverse‑sqrt<BR/>learning‑rate schedule. This architecture achieves<BR/>state‑of‑the‑art translation quality while<BR/>dramatically reducing training time.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "3603249.c3" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">3603249.c3</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Wordpiece sub‑word segmentation for<BR/>open‑vocabulary NMT</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Google&#x27;s Neural Machine Translation System:<BR/>Bridging the Gap between Human and Machine<BR/>Translation</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">GNMT adopts a data‑driven wordpiece model that<BR/>learns a fixed vocabulary of 8 k–32 k sub‑word<BR/>units shared between source and target languages.<BR/>The model uses a greedy algorithm to select<BR/>wordpieces that maximize language‑model likelihood<BR/>on the training corpus, yielding a deterministic<BR/>segmentation for any word. This representation<BR/>balances the flexibility of character models with<BR/>the efficiency of word‑level models, enabling<BR/>efficient handling of rare and out‑of‑vocabulary<BR/>words while keeping sequence lengths manageable<BR/>for the deep LSTM encoder‑decoder.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "3626819.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">3626819.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">ELMo: Deep Contextualized Word Representations</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Deep contextualized word representations</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces ELMo (Embeddings from<BR/>Language Models), a novel class of word<BR/>representations that are computed as functions of<BR/>the entire input sentence rather than fixed type<BR/>embeddings. ELMo vectors are derived from the<BR/>internal states of a deep bidirectional LSTM<BR/>language model that is pretrained on a large<BR/>monolingual corpus, enabling the representations<BR/>to capture both complex syntactic/semantic<BR/>characteristics and context‑dependent polysemy.<BR/>The authors show that ELMo can be concatenated to<BR/>any existing NLP architecture with minimal<BR/>changes, providing a universal source of<BR/>linguistic knowledge that improves<BR/>state‑of‑the‑art performance on a wide range of<BR/>downstream tasks. This contribution establishes a<BR/>conceptual framework for using deep contextualized<BR/>representations as a general paradigm in NLP.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "3626819.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">3626819.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Pretrained Bidirectional Language Model<BR/>Architecture</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Deep contextualized word representations</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors design a two‑layer bidirectional LSTM<BR/>language model that incorporates character‑level<BR/>convolutional token embeddings, two highway<BR/>layers, and a residual connection between the LSTM<BR/>layers. The model is trained on the 1‑Billion Word<BR/>Benchmark for ten epochs, achieving a<BR/>forward‑backward perplexity of 39.7 while<BR/>balancing capacity and computational cost. This<BR/>pretrained biLM serves as the backbone for<BR/>generating deep contextualized ELMo word<BR/>representations, and the pretrained weights and<BR/>extraction code are released publicly for reuse.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "16747630.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">16747630.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Integrated Gradients attribution method</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Axiomatic Attribution for Deep Networks</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces Integrated Gradients, a<BR/>feature attribution technique that computes the<BR/>path integral of a network&#x27;s gradients along the<BR/>straight‑line segment from a baseline input to the<BR/>actual input. The integral is approximated with a<BR/>Riemann sum (e.g., 50 steps) using only standard<BR/>gradient calls, so no network modification is<BR/>required. Integrated Gradients provably satisfies<BR/>the Sensitivity and Implementation Invariance<BR/>axioms as well as the Completeness property, and<BR/>can be implemented in any deep‑learning framework<BR/>such as TensorFlow.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "13029170.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">13029170.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">LIME: Local Interpretable Model‑agnostic<BR/>Explanations</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">&quot;Why Should I Trust You?&quot; Explaining the<BR/>Predictions of Any Classifier</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">LIME introduces a model‑agnostic explanation<BR/>technique that approximates any black‑box<BR/>classifier locally with an interpretable linear<BR/>model defined over a human‑understandable<BR/>representation (e.g., binary word presence). It<BR/>generates perturbed samples around the instance of<BR/>interest, weights them with an exponential kernel<BR/>based on cosine distance, and fits a sparse linear<BR/>model by selecting a small set of features via<BR/>Lasso or forward selection and estimating their<BR/>weights with weighted least squares. The resulting<BR/>explanation highlights the most influential<BR/>interpretable components, providing a faithful and<BR/>intelligible rationale for the classifier’s<BR/>prediction.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "13029170.c2" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">13029170.c2</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Open‑source LIME Software and Demonstration System</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">&quot;Why Should I Trust You?&quot; Explaining the<BR/>Predictions of Any Classifier</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors release a fully documented Python<BR/>package that implements the LIME and SP‑LIME<BR/>algorithms and provides an interactive<BR/>Jupyter‑notebook demo. The demo integrates the<BR/>explanation engine with three NLP classification<BR/>tasks (politeness detection, 20‑newsgroups<BR/>document classification, and sentiment analysis),<BR/>allowing users to input free‑form text, view<BR/>highlighted explanatory words, compare multiple<BR/>models, and iteratively perform feature cleaning<BR/>to improve classifiers. All code and documentation<BR/>are publicly available on GitHub, enabling reuse<BR/>and further research.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "12383721.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">12383721.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Large-scale politeness‑annotated request corpus</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">A computational approach to politeness with<BR/>application to social factors</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors harvested over 10,000 user‑to‑user<BR/>request utterances from Wikipedia talk pages and<BR/>Stack Exchange comments, each consisting of<BR/>exactly two sentences with the second being a<BR/>request. Each request was annotated for perceived<BR/>politeness by five independent Amazon Mechanical<BR/>Turk workers, with worker‑level z‑score<BR/>normalization and extensive vetting (U.S.<BR/>residence restriction, linguistic background<BR/>questionnaire, paraphrasing attention check). The<BR/>averaged politeness scores constitute the largest<BR/>publicly released corpus of requests with<BR/>fine‑grained politeness annotations, supporting<BR/>downstream linguistic analysis and classifier<BR/>training.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "12383721.c7" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">12383721.c7</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Public release of politeness detection dataset and<BR/>software</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">A computational approach to politeness with<BR/>application to social factors</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors make publicly available the large<BR/>politeness‑annotated request corpus together with<BR/>the feature‑extraction scripts and the trained<BR/>support‑vector‑machine classifier. This release<BR/>enables other researchers to replicate the<BR/>experiments, benchmark new models, and apply<BR/>politeness detection to novel online communication<BR/>data. The resources are provided as a reusable<BR/>dataset and as open‑source software tools hosted<BR/>online.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "6628106.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">6628106.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Bias‑Correction for Exponential Moving Averages in<BR/>Adam</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Adam: A Method for Stochastic Optimization</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors observe that the exponential moving<BR/>averages used to estimate the first (mean) and<BR/>second (uncentered variance) moments of stochastic<BR/>gradients are biased toward zero when initialized<BR/>with zero vectors. They derive closed‑form<BR/>correction factors that divide the raw moment<BR/>estimates by (1 − β₁^t) and (1 − β₂^t),<BR/>respectively, yielding unbiased moment estimates<BR/>even for decay rates close to one or highly sparse<BR/>gradients. The corrected estimates are<BR/>incorporated into the Adam update rule and<BR/>experimentally shown to improve stability and<BR/>convergence.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "6628106.c2-1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">6628106.c2-1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">O(√T) Regret Bound for Adam</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Adam: A Method for Stochastic Optimization</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper proves that, under the online convex<BR/>optimization setting with convex loss functions,<BR/>bounded gradients, a stepsize schedule α_t ∝ 1/√t,<BR/>and exponentially decaying first‑moment<BR/>coefficients β1,t, the Adam optimizer attains a<BR/>regret bounded by O(√T). The proof leverages<BR/>bias‑corrected moment estimates and adapts<BR/>techniques from adaptive gradient methods to<BR/>establish the sublinear regret guarantee.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "6628106.c2-2" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">6628106.c2-2</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Average Regret Convergence to Zero</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Adam: A Method for Stochastic Optimization</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">As a corollary of the O(√T) regret bound, the<BR/>paper shows that the average regret of Adam,<BR/>defined as the cumulative regret divided by T,<BR/>converges to zero as T → ∞, establishing<BR/>asymptotic optimality of the algorithm for convex<BR/>stochastic optimization.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "6628106.c5-1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">6628106.c5-1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Invariance of Adam&#x27;s Effective Step Size to<BR/>Diagonal Rescaling of Gradients</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Adam: A Method for Stochastic Optimization</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper proves that Adam&#x27;s update rule yields an<BR/>effective step size that is unchanged when the<BR/>gradient vector is multiplied element‑wise by any<BR/>positive diagonal matrix. By examining the<BR/>bias‑corrected first‑moment estimate m̂_t and<BR/>second‑moment estimate v̂_t, the authors show that<BR/>scaling each coordinate of the gradient by a<BR/>constant c scales m̂_t by c and v̂_t by c², which<BR/>cancel in the ratio m̂_t/√v̂_t, leaving the<BR/>parameter update magnitude invariant. This<BR/>property explains Adam&#x27;s robustness to differing<BR/>gradient magnitude scales across parameters.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "6628106.c5-2" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">6628106.c5-2</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Upper Bound on Per‑Parameter Update Magnitude<BR/>Proportional to Global Stepsize α</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Adam: A Method for Stochastic Optimization</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors prove that each parameter update<BR/>produced by Adam satisfies |Δ_t| ≤ α, where α is<BR/>the global stepsize hyper‑parameter. By<BR/>substituting the bias‑corrected first‑moment<BR/>estimate \hat{m}_t and second‑moment estimate<BR/>\hat{v}_t into the effective stepsize formula Δ_t<BR/>= α·\hat{m}_t / (√\hat{v}_t + ε) and using the<BR/>fact that the (uncentered) second moment always<BR/>dominates the squared first moment, they show that<BR/>the ratio is bounded by 1. This yields a<BR/>trust‑region‑like guarantee that the step size<BR/>cannot exceed the prescribed α, simplifying<BR/>hyper‑parameter selection.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "6628106.c5-3" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">6628106.c5-3</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Signal-to-Noise Ratio Interpretation and Automatic<BR/>Annealing of Step Sizes</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Adam: A Method for Stochastic Optimization</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper interprets the bias‑corrected<BR/>first‑moment estimate \(\hat{m}_t\) divided by the<BR/>square‑root of the bias‑corrected second‑moment<BR/>estimate \(\sqrt{\hat{v}_t}\) as a signal‑to‑noise<BR/>ratio (SNR) of the stochastic gradient. Because<BR/>the effective step size \(\Delta_t = \alpha \cdot<BR/>\hat{m}_t / (\sqrt{\hat{v}_t}+\epsilon)\) is<BR/>proportional to this SNR, when the SNR is low<BR/>(e.g., near a minimum where gradient variance<BR/>dominates) the step size automatically shrinks,<BR/>providing an implicit annealing mechanism without<BR/>an explicit learning‑rate schedule.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "6628106.c6" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">6628106.c6</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Unified Adaptive Gradient Method Framework</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Adam: A Method for Stochastic Optimization</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper synthesizes a conceptual framework that<BR/>positions Adam as a unifying adaptive optimizer.<BR/>It demonstrates that Adam subsumes the<BR/>sparse‑gradient handling of AdaGrad and the<BR/>non‑stationary adaptability of RMSProp, and it<BR/>formally relates Adam to AdaDelta, vSGD, and<BR/>natural‑gradient methods by expressing their<BR/>update rules within a common mathematical<BR/>formulation. This unified view clarifies how<BR/>different adaptive learning‑rate schemes can be<BR/>derived as special cases or limits of Adam’s<BR/>moment‑based updates.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "229371222.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">229371222.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Iterative generative ProofWriter model for<BR/>faithful natural-language proof generation</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">ProofWriter: Generating Implications, Proofs, and<BR/>Abductive Statements over Natural Language</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">ProofWriter fine‑tunes a T5‑11B text‑to‑text<BR/>transformer to generate logical implications and<BR/>human‑readable proofs over natural‑language<BR/>theories by repeatedly applying a 1‑step<BR/>implication generator, appending each derived fact<BR/>to the context, and assembling deeper proofs from<BR/>these fragments. The iterative forward‑chaining<BR/>loop guarantees that every proof step corresponds<BR/>to a model decision, yielding proofs that are<BR/>faithful to the model’s internal reasoning.<BR/>Empirical evaluation on the RuleTaker,<BR/>Birds‑Electricity, and ParaRules datasets<BR/>demonstrates state‑of‑the‑art proof accuracy (+9 %<BR/>absolute over PRover) and robust generalisation to<BR/>reasoning depths unseen during training.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#fde0c5"];
    "204838007.c9-1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">204838007.c9-1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Scaling model size up to 11 B parameters</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Exploring the Limits of Transfer Learning with a<BR/>Unified Text-to-Text Transformer</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors systematically increase the number of<BR/>parameters of the T5 encoder‑decoder Transformer<BR/>from the baseline 220 M to 770 M, 3 B and finally<BR/>11 B, keeping the architecture, pre‑training<BR/>objective, data, and training hyper‑parameters<BR/>constant. Each model is pre‑trained on the C4<BR/>corpus and fine‑tuned on a wide suite of NLP<BR/>benchmarks. The results show consistent<BR/>performance gains across tasks as model size<BR/>grows, confirming that larger models yield better<BR/>language understanding and generation<BR/>capabilities.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "204838007.c11" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">204838007.c11</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Release of T5 model checkpoints, code, and C4<BR/>dataset</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Exploring the Limits of Transfer Learning with a<BR/>Unified Text-to-Text Transformer</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors publicly release pre‑trained T5 model<BR/>checkpoints for five model sizes (Small, Base,<BR/>Large, 3 B, 11 B), the full TensorFlow‑based<BR/>training and evaluation codebase, and the Colossal<BR/>Clean Crawled Corpus (C4) dataset. These artifacts<BR/>enable the research community to reproduce the<BR/>experiments, fine‑tune the models on downstream<BR/>tasks, and build new systems using the same<BR/>unified text‑to‑text framework. The release is<BR/>accompanied by documentation and integration with<BR/>TensorFlow Datasets for easy access.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "211126663.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">211126663.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Synthetic RuleTaker dataset suite</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Transformers as Soft Reasoners over Language</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors construct five large‑scale synthetic<BR/>benchmark datasets (D=0, D≤1, D≤2, D≤3, DMax),<BR/>each containing 100 k examples of randomly<BR/>generated rule‑based logical theories. For every<BR/>theory they perform exhaustive forward chaining to<BR/>obtain all derivable facts, label true statements,<BR/>generate false statements under a closed‑world<BR/>assumption, and render facts, rules, and queries<BR/>as templated English sentences. The datasets<BR/>systematically vary the maximum inference depth<BR/>(up to five steps) and include both negated and<BR/>non‑negated variants, providing a controlled<BR/>resource for training and evaluating neural models<BR/>on multi‑step logical reasoning over language.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "211126663.c2" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">211126663.c2</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">RuleTaker: RoBERTa‑large fine‑tuned as a soft<BR/>theorem prover</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Transformers as Soft Reasoners over Language</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors fine‑tune a pretrained RoBERTa‑large<BR/>model (additionally fine‑tuned on the RACE<BR/>reading‑comprehension dataset) to predict the<BR/>truth value of a query given a natural‑language<BR/>context consisting of facts and<BR/>conjunctive‑implication rules. The resulting<BR/>model, called RuleTaker, emulates the input‑output<BR/>behavior of a formal theorem prover, operating<BR/>directly on language without any explicit symbolic<BR/>manipulation, and achieves near‑perfect accuracy<BR/>on synthetic rule‑reasoning benchmarks as well as<BR/>strong zero‑shot transfer to hand‑authored and<BR/>paraphrased rulebases.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "222141025.c0-1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">222141025.c0-1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">PROVER Multi-Module Transformer Architecture for<BR/>Joint QA and Proof Generation</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">PROVER: Proof Generation for Interpretable<BR/>Reasoning over Rules</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">PROVER is a neural system built on a shared<BR/>RoBERTa‑large encoder that simultaneously performs<BR/>binary question answering over natural‑language<BR/>rule bases and constructs explicit proof graphs.<BR/>It consists of three parallel modules: a QA<BR/>classifier that predicts the answer, a Node<BR/>classifier that selects the subset of facts,<BR/>rules, and a Negation‑As‑Failure (NAF) node<BR/>required for the proof, and an Edge classifier<BR/>that predicts directed edges between the selected<BR/>nodes to form a proof graph. The three modules are<BR/>trained jointly with a combined cross‑entropy<BR/>loss, enabling shared representations useful for<BR/>both answer prediction and structured proof<BR/>construction.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "198953378.c4" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">198953378.c4</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">RoBERTa pretraining recipe and state‑of‑the‑art<BR/>benchmark results</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">RoBERTa: A Robustly Optimized BERT Pretraining<BR/>Approach</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors introduce RoBERTa, a robustly<BR/>optimized BERT pretraining configuration that<BR/>combines (i) dynamic masking, (ii) removal of the<BR/>next‑sentence prediction (NSP) objective, (iii)<BR/>large mini‑batch training with appropriate<BR/>learning‑rate scaling, (iv) training on<BR/>full‑length sequences throughout, and (v) a<BR/>byte‑level BPE vocabulary. Using this recipe they<BR/>train BERT‑BASE and BERT‑LARGE models for up to<BR/>500 K steps on up to 160 GB of public text<BR/>(including the CC‑NEWS corpus). The resulting<BR/>models achieve new best scores on GLUE, SQuAD<BR/>1.1/2.0 and RACE, surpassing prior work such as<BR/>XLNet without multi‑task finetuning or extra data.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "198953378.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">198953378.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Discovery of BERT under‑training and four simple<BR/>training improvements (RoBERTa recipe)</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">RoBERTa: A Robustly Optimized BERT Pretraining<BR/>Approach</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">By replicating BERT pretraining, the authors show<BR/>that the original BERT model was trained for<BR/>insufficient steps and that its performance can be<BR/>substantially improved by (i) training for many<BR/>more updates with larger mini‑batches, (ii)<BR/>removing the next‑sentence prediction (NSP)<BR/>objective, (iii) feeding longer input sequences<BR/>(full‑sentence inputs), and (iv) using dynamic<BR/>masking instead of a static mask. These four<BR/>modifications together define the RoBERTa training<BR/>recipe, which achieves state‑of‑the‑art results on<BR/>GLUE, SQuAD and RACE without extra data or<BR/>multi‑task finetuning.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "198953378.c7" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">198953378.c7</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Open‑source implementation and pretrained<BR/>checkpoints</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">RoBERTa: A Robustly Optimized BERT Pretraining<BR/>Approach</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors release a full PyTorch/Fairseq<BR/>codebase that re‑implements BERT pretraining and<BR/>downstream fine‑tuning, together with pretrained<BR/>RoBERTa checkpoints for both BASE and LARGE<BR/>configurations. The released artifacts include<BR/>data preprocessing, dynamic masking, large‑batch<BR/>training, mixed‑precision support, and a<BR/>byte‑level BPE tokenizer, enabling reproducibility<BR/>of the RoBERTa recipe and allowing the community<BR/>to use state‑of‑the‑art models without retraining<BR/>from scratch.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "222141025.c0-2" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">222141025.c0-2</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Constrained Joint Training Regime with Edge<BR/>Masking and Global Semantic Constraints</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">PROVER: Proof Generation for Interpretable<BR/>Reasoning over Rules</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">PROVER jointly predicts binary labels for node<BR/>presence and edge existence while masking out<BR/>impossible edges (self‑loops, fact‑to‑fact,<BR/>rule‑to‑fact, and edges involving absent nodes)<BR/>during training, and combines the QA, Node, and<BR/>Edge binary cross‑entropy losses into a single<BR/>objective. At inference, an Integer Linear<BR/>Programming (ILP) solver selects a subset of edges<BR/>that maximizes the summed edge probabilities while<BR/>satisfying semantic edge constraints and a<BR/>max‑flow connectivity constraint, guaranteeing<BR/>that only valid, connected proof graphs are<BR/>produced.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "222141025.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">222141025.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Graph‑Based Proof Representation with Global<BR/>Constraints</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">PROVER: Proof Generation for Interpretable<BR/>Reasoning over Rules</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper formalizes proofs for natural‑language<BR/>rule reasoning as directed graphs whose nodes are<BR/>facts, rules, or a special Negation‑As‑Failure<BR/>(NAF) node and whose edges encode permissible<BR/>inference directions (fact→rule or rule→rule).<BR/>Three proof types are defined (successful with<BR/>NAF, successful without NAF, failed) and during<BR/>training impossible edges (self‑loops,<BR/>fact‑to‑fact, rule‑to‑fact) are masked to simplify<BR/>learning. At inference time an Integer Linear<BR/>Program selects a subset of edges that maximizes<BR/>the model&#x27;s edge scores while enforcing global<BR/>constraints such as graph connectivity and the<BR/>semantic edge restrictions, guaranteeing that the<BR/>generated proof is valid.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "211126663.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">211126663.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">RuleTaker soft theorem‑proving task formulation</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Transformers as Soft Reasoners over Language</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper defines a new reasoning task in which a<BR/>transformer model receives a context consisting of<BR/>natural‑language facts and conjunctive‑implication<BR/>rules and must answer a true/false query that may<BR/>require multi‑step deduction. By expressing the<BR/>knowledge base directly in English rather than a<BR/>formal logical language, the task reframes logical<BR/>inference as a &quot;soft theorem proving&quot; problem that<BR/>can be learned end‑to‑end. This formulation<BR/>isolates the I/O behavior of a deductive reasoner<BR/>and enables systematic evaluation of neural models<BR/>on controlled inference depths.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "218487535.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">218487535.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Module-wise Faithfulness Framework for Neural<BR/>Module Networks</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Obtaining Faithful Interpretations from<BR/>Compositional Neural Networks</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces a systematic framework to<BR/>evaluate whether each neural module in a Neural<BR/>Module Network (NMN) performs its intended atomic<BR/>reasoning operation. It defines the notion of<BR/>module-wise faithfulness and proposes quantitative<BR/>metrics: precision/recall/F1 for visual NMNs based<BR/>on aligned bounding-box annotations, and<BR/>cross-entropy for textual NMNs based on gold span<BR/>annotations. The framework enables rigorous,<BR/>reproducible assessment of interpretability beyond<BR/>ad-hoc qualitative inspection.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "3130692.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">3130692.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Dynamic Neural Module Network (D‑NMN) architecture</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Learning to Compose Neural Networks for Question<BR/>Answering</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper proposes a Dynamic Neural Module Network<BR/>that jointly learns a set of composable neural<BR/>modules and a layout predictor which assembles a<BR/>question‑specific deep network on the fly. The<BR/>system is trained end‑to‑end from (world,<BR/>question, answer) triples without any explicit<BR/>supervision of the network layouts, thereby<BR/>unifying visual question answering and structured<BR/>knowledge‑base QA under a single differentiable<BR/>framework. The architecture combines<BR/>attention‑based modules, a dependency‑parse‑driven<BR/>layout candidate generator, and a REINFORCE‑based<BR/>policy to select layouts, enabling expressive<BR/>instance‑specific computation.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "3130692.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">3130692.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Joint learning algorithm for modules and layouts</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Learning to Compose Neural Networks for Question<BR/>Answering</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces a training procedure that<BR/>simultaneously learns the parameters of a set of<BR/>neural modules and the discrete layout predictor<BR/>that assembles them into question-specific<BR/>networks. Module parameters are updated with<BR/>standard back‑propagation, while the layout<BR/>predictor is trained with a REINFORCE<BR/>policy‑gradient where the reward is the negative<BR/>log‑likelihood of the correct answer. This enables<BR/>end‑to‑end learning from only (world, question,<BR/>answer) triples without any layout supervision.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "3130692.c2" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">3130692.c2</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Neural module inventory for visual and structured<BR/>domains</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Learning to Compose Neural Networks for Question<BR/>Answering</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper defines a set of six composable neural<BR/>modules—lookup, find, relate, and, describe, and<BR/>exists—each with explicit input and output type<BR/>constraints (Attention or Labels). These modules<BR/>extend the standard soft‑attention mechanism to<BR/>operate both on convolutional image feature maps<BR/>and on vector embeddings of entities from<BR/>knowledge bases, providing differentiable<BR/>analogues of logical operations such as set<BR/>intersection and existential quantification.<BR/>Modules share global parameters across instances<BR/>while allowing lexical specialization via<BR/>per‑module parameter arguments, enabling reuse and<BR/>efficient learning.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "3130692.c3" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">3130692.c3</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Layout prediction via dependency‑parse candidates<BR/>and LSTM‑MLP scoring</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Learning to Compose Neural Networks for Question<BR/>Answering</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces a method that converts a<BR/>question into a small set of candidate network<BR/>layouts by first parsing the sentence with a<BR/>Stanford dependency parser, then mapping nouns,<BR/>verbs, and prepositional phrases to predefined<BR/>module fragments. Each candidate layout is scored<BR/>by concatenating an LSTM encoding of the whole<BR/>question with a feature vector describing the<BR/>layout and feeding the result through a multilayer<BR/>perceptron; the scores are normalized to a<BR/>distribution p(z|x). During training the layout is<BR/>sampled and the scoring network is updated with a<BR/>REINFORCE policy‑gradient signal, allowing the<BR/>model to learn layout selection without explicit<BR/>layout supervision.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "18682.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">18682.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">End-to-End Module Networks (N2NMN) architecture</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Learning to Reason: End-to-End Module Networks for<BR/>Visual Question Answering</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces End-to-End Module Networks<BR/>(N2NMN), a visual question answering system that<BR/>dynamically assembles a question‑specific neural<BR/>network from a library of co‑attentive modules. A<BR/>sequence‑to‑sequence controller with attention<BR/>predicts a layout expression in reverse‑Polish<BR/>notation directly from the raw question, and each<BR/>module receives a soft‑attention‑derived textual<BR/>vector, eliminating hand‑crafted word assignments.<BR/>Training proceeds in two stages: behavioral<BR/>cloning from expert layouts provides a strong<BR/>initialization, followed by REINFORCE‑style<BR/>policy‑gradient fine‑tuning of the layout policy<BR/>and module parameters. The resulting model<BR/>achieves state‑of‑the‑art performance on CLEVR and<BR/>competitive results on VQA and SHAPES.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "18682.c2" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">18682.c2</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Co‑attentive neural modules for visual reasoning</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Learning to Reason: End-to-End Module Networks for<BR/>Visual Question Answering</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper defines a library of differentiable<BR/>neural modules (e.g., find, filter, relocate, and,<BR/>or, describe, compare, count, exist) that operate<BR/>on zero, one, or two image‑attention maps together<BR/>with visual feature maps and a<BR/>soft‑attention‑derived textual vector. Each module<BR/>produces either a refined attention map or a<BR/>distribution over answer candidates, providing<BR/>reusable functional primitives for compositional<BR/>visual question answering. The modules are<BR/>designed to be assembled dynamically according to<BR/>a layout predicted from the question, enabling<BR/>end‑to‑end training of both module parameters and<BR/>the layout policy.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "202565945.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">202565945.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Self-assembling Neural Modular Network for<BR/>Text-based Multi-hop QA</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Self-Assembling Modular Networks for Interpretable<BR/>Multi-Hop Reasoning</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces the first Neural Modular<BR/>Network (NMN) that self‑assembles a reasoning<BR/>architecture for unstructured text. A recurrent<BR/>controller reads a HotpotQA question, generates<BR/>soft sub‑question vectors, and predicts a soft<BR/>layout over four language‑oriented modules (Find,<BR/>Relocate, Compare, NoOp). The selected modules are<BR/>executed on a differentiable stack that stores<BR/>intermediate attention maps, enabling end‑to‑end<BR/>gradient‑based training without reinforcement<BR/>learning. This design provides flexible,<BR/>compositional reasoning over long contexts<BR/>containing multiple evidence pieces and yields<BR/>state‑of‑the‑art performance on HotpotQA and its<BR/>adversarial variant.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "202565945.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">202565945.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Four language‑oriented NMN modules for textual<BR/>reasoning</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Self-Assembling Modular Networks for Interpretable<BR/>Multi-Hop Reasoning</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces four novel neural<BR/>modules—Find, Relocate, Compare, and<BR/>NoOp—specifically designed for multi‑hop question<BR/>answering over unstructured text. Find performs<BR/>bidirectional attention between the question and<BR/>the context to produce an attention map over<BR/>answer spans. Relocate consumes the attention from<BR/>a previous step, extracts a bridge‑entity<BR/>representation, and searches the context for the<BR/>next answer. Compare aggregates two attention maps<BR/>and evaluates relational properties between the<BR/>extracted entities. NoOp passes the current<BR/>network state unchanged, allowing the controller<BR/>to terminate reasoning. These modules replace the<BR/>image‑centric operations used in prior NMNs and<BR/>enable end‑to‑end differentiable multi‑step<BR/>reasoning for HotpotQA.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "202565945.c2" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">202565945.c2</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Controller RNN with soft layout prediction and<BR/>sub‑question attention</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Self-Assembling Modular Networks for Interpretable<BR/>Multi-Hop Reasoning</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">A recurrent controller reads the encoded HotpotQA<BR/>question, computes a soft attention distribution<BR/>over its words to produce a sub‑question vector,<BR/>and at each reasoning step predicts a probability<BR/>distribution over the four NMN modules (Find,<BR/>Relocate, Compare, NoOp). The soft layout weights<BR/>the outputs of all modules, enabling<BR/>differentiable program execution without<BR/>reinforcement learning, while the sub‑question<BR/>vector updates the controller hidden state for the<BR/>next step, allowing fully end‑to‑end training of<BR/>the modular reasoning network.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "53178856.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">53178856.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">NLVR2: large‑scale natural‑language visual<BR/>reasoning dataset and benchmark</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">A Corpus for Reasoning About Natural Language<BR/>Grounded in Photographs</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces NLVR2, a publicly released<BR/>corpus of 107,292 examples consisting of 29,680<BR/>distinct English captions each paired with two<BR/>real‑world photographs (127,502 unique images).<BR/>Each caption appears with multiple image‑pair<BR/>instances that are labeled True or False in a<BR/>balanced fashion, defining a binary verification<BR/>task that requires joint reasoning over language<BR/>and two images. Fixed train/dev/public‑test<BR/>splits, a consistency metric, and baseline<BR/>evaluations are provided, establishing NLVR2 as a<BR/>new benchmark for compositional visual reasoning.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "53178856.c8" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">53178856.c8</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Public release of NLVR2 dataset, collection<BR/>pipeline, and evaluation code</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">A Corpus for Reasoning About Natural Language<BR/>Grounded in Photographs</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors make publicly available the full NLVR2<BR/>corpus (train, development, and public‑test<BR/>splits), the end‑to‑end image‑collection and<BR/>caption‑writing pipelines, and the source code for<BR/>baseline and adapted visual‑reasoning models<BR/>together with evaluation scripts at<BR/>http://lil.nlp.cornell.edu/nlvr/. This release<BR/>enables reproducibility, benchmarking, and further<BR/>research on compositional visual reasoning with<BR/>real photographs.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "67855846.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">67855846.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Creation of the DROP dataset (96,567 QA pairs with<BR/>numbers, spans, dates)</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">DROP: A Reading Comprehension Benchmark Requiring<BR/>Discrete Reasoning Over Paragraphs</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors construct a large‑scale English<BR/>reading‑comprehension benchmark consisting of<BR/>96,567 question‑answer pairs drawn from Wikipedia<BR/>passages. Answers are limited to text spans,<BR/>numeric values, or dates, and the questions are<BR/>designed to require discrete reasoning such as<BR/>addition, subtraction, counting, sorting, and<BR/>coreference resolution. An adversarial<BR/>crowdsourcing pipeline forces workers to produce<BR/>questions that a baseline BiDAF model cannot<BR/>answer, ensuring high difficulty. The dataset is<BR/>split by passage into training, development, and<BR/>test sets and released publicly as a benchmark for<BR/>evaluating discrete reasoning over paragraphs.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "67855846.c6" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">67855846.c6</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Public release of the DROP benchmark, baseline<BR/>implementations, and evaluation leaderboard</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">DROP: A Reading Comprehension Benchmark Requiring<BR/>Discrete Reasoning Over Paragraphs</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors publicly release the DROP dataset<BR/>together with reference implementations of<BR/>baseline reading‑comprehension models (BiDAF,<BR/>QANet, QANet+ELMo, BERT) and the NAQANet model,<BR/>and provide a hidden‑test leaderboard hosted at<BR/>https://allennlp.org/drop. This release supplies<BR/>the research community with the data, code, and<BR/>evaluation infrastructure needed to develop and<BR/>compare systems that perform discrete reasoning<BR/>over paragraphs.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "7053611.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">7053611.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Input‑gradient explanations match LIME fidelity<BR/>and are computationally efficient</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Right for the Right Reasons: Training<BR/>Differentiable Models by Constraining their<BR/>Explanations</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper demonstrates that the gradient of a<BR/>differentiable model’s output with respect to its<BR/>inputs yields local, feature‑level explanations<BR/>that closely resemble those produced by the<BR/>model‑agnostic LIME method across toy, text, and<BR/>image datasets. By visualizing the magnitude of<BR/>input gradients, the same salient pixels or words<BR/>identified by LIME are recovered, while the<BR/>gradient can be obtained with a single backward<BR/>pass, making it orders of magnitude faster than<BR/>LIME’s perturb‑and‑fit procedure. This establishes<BR/>input‑gradient explanations as a faithful and<BR/>scalable alternative for interpreting neural<BR/>networks.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "7053611.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">7053611.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Gradient‑based explanation regularization (RRR)</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Right for the Right Reasons: Training<BR/>Differentiable Models by Constraining their<BR/>Explanations</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors introduce a differentiable loss term<BR/>that augments the standard cross‑entropy and<BR/>weight‑decay objectives with a penalty on the<BR/>magnitude of input‑gradient components at feature<BR/>dimensions marked as irrelevant by a binary<BR/>annotation matrix A. By shrinking gradients in<BR/>these regions, training steers the model toward<BR/>decision boundaries that respect domain knowledge<BR/>while preserving classification accuracy. The<BR/>regularizer is compatible with any gradient‑based<BR/>optimizer and can be applied to arbitrary<BR/>differentiable models.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "7053611.c3-1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">7053611.c3-1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Explanation‑regularized models retain accuracy<BR/>under distribution shift</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Right for the Right Reasons: Training<BR/>Differentiable Models by Constraining their<BR/>Explanations</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors augment the standard cross‑entropy<BR/>loss with a penalty on input‑gradient magnitudes<BR/>for features marked as irrelevant, training neural<BR/>classifiers that are constrained to rely on<BR/>domain‑relevant cues. Across four domains—a<BR/>synthetic 5×5×3 color dataset, a composite<BR/>Iris‑Cancer tabular set, the 20 Newsgroups text<BR/>classification task, and a Decoy MNIST image<BR/>set—they show that models trained with this<BR/>gradient‑based explanation regularization maintain<BR/>or recover baseline test accuracy when the<BR/>training‑test distribution differs (e.g., when<BR/>confounding features are removed). This<BR/>demonstrates that constraining explanations<BR/>improves robustness to covariate shift caused by<BR/>spurious correlations.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "7053611.c4" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">7053611.c4</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Explanation regularization improves data<BR/>efficiency</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Right for the Right Reasons: Training<BR/>Differentiable Models by Constraining their<BR/>Explanations</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors empirically demonstrate on a synthetic<BR/>5×5×3 RGB toy color dataset that adding a<BR/>gradient‑based explanation penalty (RRR) or the<BR/>unsupervised find‑another‑explanation penalty<BR/>enables a model to achieve a target accuracy with<BR/>far fewer labeled training examples than a<BR/>baseline model without such regularization. By<BR/>varying the number of training samples and<BR/>measuring test accuracy, they show that<BR/>constraining explanations to align with domain<BR/>knowledge reduces the sample complexity of<BR/>learning. The analysis also compares the two<BR/>regularization strategies and discusses their<BR/>impact on data efficiency.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "7053611.c5" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">7053611.c5</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Open‑source implementation of<BR/>Right‑for‑the‑Right‑Reasons (RRR) training</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Right for the Right Reasons: Training<BR/>Differentiable Models by Constraining their<BR/>Explanations</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors release a publicly available software<BR/>package (https://github.com/dtak/rrr) that<BR/>implements the full RRR pipeline: generation of<BR/>input‑gradient explanations, the<BR/>explanation‑regularization loss that penalises<BR/>gradients on annotated irrelevant features, and<BR/>the find‑another‑explanation iterative algorithm<BR/>for discovering diverse classifiers. The code is<BR/>built on the autograd automatic‑differentiation<BR/>library and uses the Adam optimizer to train<BR/>two‑hidden‑layer multilayer perceptrons,<BR/>reproducing all experiments reported in the paper<BR/>and enabling other researchers to apply the method<BR/>to new models and datasets.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "67855860.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">67855860.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Large‑scale empirical benchmark of attention as<BR/>explanation</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Attention is not Explanation</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper conducts a systematic, large‑scale<BR/>empirical study of standard attention mechanisms<BR/>across nine NLP tasks (binary sentiment, IMDB, ADR<BR/>tweets, 20 News, AG News, MIMIC ICD‑9, CNN QA,<BR/>bAbI, SNLI) and three encoder families (Bi‑LSTM,<BR/>CNN, average‑embedding). For each dataset‑encoder<BR/>pair it quantifies (i) the Kendall‑τ correlation<BR/>between learned attention weights and two<BR/>alternative feature‑importance signals (input<BR/>gradients and leave‑one‑out erasure) and (ii) the<BR/>effect of altering attention distributions on<BR/>model predictions using total variation distance<BR/>and Jensen‑Shannon divergence, thereby providing<BR/>the first comprehensive benchmark of the<BR/>explanatory value of attention.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "67855860.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">67855860.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Weak and inconsistent correlation between<BR/>attention weights and feature‑importance measures</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Attention is not Explanation</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors compute Kendall‑τ rank correlation<BR/>between attention scores generated by standard<BR/>additive (Bahdanau) and scaled‑dot‑product<BR/>(Vaswani) attention mechanisms and two established<BR/>feature‑importance baselines: input‑gradient<BR/>attributions and leave‑one‑out (erasure) scores.<BR/>Across nine NLP tasks using a Bi‑LSTM encoder, the<BR/>average τ never exceeds 0.36 and is often<BR/>statistically insignificant, whereas a simple<BR/>average‑embedding encoder yields substantially<BR/>higher τ (~0.6). This analysis demonstrates that,<BR/>for contextual encoders, attention weights are not<BR/>reliable proxies for the inputs that most drive<BR/>model predictions.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "67855860.c2" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">67855860.c2</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Random permutation of attention weights often<BR/>leaves predictions unchanged</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Attention is not Explanation</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors randomly permute the attention weight<BR/>vector produced by standard additive or scaled<BR/>dot‑product attention for each test instance and<BR/>measure the resulting change in model output using<BR/>Total Variation Distance (TVD). Across nine NLP<BR/>tasks (sentiment classification, QA, NLI) and<BR/>three encoder families (BiLSTM, CNN,<BR/>average‑embedding) they find many instances where<BR/>even large attention weights can be shuffled with<BR/>only negligible impact on the prediction,<BR/>indicating that the original attention heatmap is<BR/>not uniquely tied to the output.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "67855860.c3" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">67855860.c3</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Adversarial attention optimization for<BR/>counterfactual explanations</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Attention is not Explanation</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper formulates a constrained optimization<BR/>problem that seeks attention weight vectors<BR/>maximally dissimilar (high Jensen‑Shannon<BR/>divergence) from the model‑learned attention while<BR/>keeping the model output within a small<BR/>total‑variation distance (≤ 0.01 for<BR/>classification, ≤ 0.05 for QA). The objective is<BR/>solved with the Adam optimizer and includes a<BR/>diversity term to obtain multiple, diverse<BR/>adversarial attention distributions per instance.<BR/>Empirical experiments across nine NLP tasks show<BR/>that many distinct attention heatmaps can be<BR/>generated that leave the prediction virtually<BR/>unchanged, demonstrating that standard attention<BR/>weights are not unique explanations for model<BR/>outputs.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "67855860.c4" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">67855860.c4</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Open‑source codebase and interactive visualisation<BR/>suite</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Attention is not Explanation</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors release a fully reproducible<BR/>implementation of all models, datasets, and<BR/>analysis pipelines used in the study, hosted at<BR/>https://github.com/successar/AttentionExplanation.<BR/>In addition, they provide an online interactive<BR/>interface that lets users explore attention<BR/>heatmaps, correlation histograms, and adversarial<BR/>examples for each dataset and encoder<BR/>configuration. This resource enables other<BR/>researchers to replicate the experiments, extend<BR/>the analysis, and benchmark future work on<BR/>attention as explanation.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "67855860.c5" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">67855860.c5</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Position statement cautioning against treating<BR/>attention as explanation</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Attention is not Explanation</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors assert that standard attention modules<BR/>in neural NLP models should not be interpreted as<BR/>providing meaningful explanations of model<BR/>predictions. This stance is grounded in extensive<BR/>empirical evidence showing (i) weak and<BR/>inconsistent correlation between attention weights<BR/>and established feature‑importance measures<BR/>(gradient saliency and leave‑one‑out erasure) and<BR/>(ii) the existence of many counterfactual<BR/>attention distributions that leave predictions<BR/>virtually unchanged. Consequently, they advise<BR/>practitioners to avoid presenting attention<BR/>heatmaps as definitive rationales and to consider<BR/>alternative interpretability techniques.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "215416110.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">215416110.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Taxonomy of Faithfulness Evaluation Based on Three<BR/>Core Assumptions</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Towards Faithfully Interpretable NLP Systems: How<BR/>Should We Define and Evaluate Faithfulness?</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper surveys existing faithfulness evaluation<BR/>methods for NLP models and organizes them around<BR/>three explicit assumptions: (1) the Model<BR/>Assumption – identical predictions imply identical<BR/>reasoning; (2) the Prediction Assumption – similar<BR/>inputs should lead to similar reasoning; and (3)<BR/>the Linearity Assumption – input parts contribute<BR/>independently to the decision. By making these<BR/>assumptions explicit, the authors provide a<BR/>unified conceptual taxonomy that clarifies how<BR/>disparate evaluation techniques are related and<BR/>what notion of faithfulness they implicitly adopt.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "215416110.c2" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">215416110.c2</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Critique of Binary Faithfulness and Proposal of<BR/>Graded Faithfulness Criteria</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Towards Faithfully Interpretable NLP Systems: How<BR/>Should We Define and Evaluate Faithfulness?</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper argues that treating faithfulness of NLP<BR/>explanations as a binary property is unrealistic<BR/>because explanations are approximations of highly<BR/>non‑linear model reasoning and therefore cannot be<BR/>perfectly faithful for all inputs. It shows that<BR/>existing binary evaluations mainly serve to<BR/>falsify methods via counter‑examples and that such<BR/>a strict view hinders practical progress. To<BR/>address this, the authors propose a graded,<BR/>&quot;grayscale&quot; notion of faithfulness that quantifies<BR/>the degree to which an explanation aligns with the<BR/>model’s reasoning, enabling nuanced assessment<BR/>across models, tasks, and input regions.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "215416110.c3" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">215416110.c3</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Explicit Distinction Between Faithfulness and<BR/>Plausibility</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Towards Faithfully Interpretable NLP Systems: How<BR/>Should We Define and Evaluate Faithfulness?</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors highlight that the interpretability<BR/>literature often conflates faithfulness (the<BR/>degree to which an explanation mirrors the model&#x27;s<BR/>actual reasoning) with plausibility (the degree to<BR/>which an explanation appears convincing to<BR/>humans). They analyze prior work to show how this<BR/>conflation can lead to harmful outcomes in<BR/>high‑stakes applications and argue for a clear,<BR/>separate treatment of the two criteria in both<BR/>research and practice.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "215416110.c4" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">215416110.c4</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Two-Axis Graded Faithfulness Evaluation Framework</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Towards Faithfully Interpretable NLP Systems: How<BR/>Should We Define and Evaluate Faithfulness?</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper proposes a future research agenda that<BR/>evaluates explanation faithfulness along two<BR/>complementary dimensions: (1) across models and<BR/>tasks, measuring the degree of faithfulness for<BR/>each specific model‑task pair, and (2) across the<BR/>input space, measuring faithfulness locally for<BR/>neighborhoods of similar inputs or individual<BR/>instances. This two‑axis conceptual framework<BR/>replaces the prevailing binary notion of<BR/>faithfulness with a nuanced, context‑dependent<BR/>assessment that can capture partial but useful<BR/>alignment between explanations and model<BR/>reasoning. The authors also outline procedural<BR/>directions for operationalising these axes in<BR/>empirical studies, encouraging the community to<BR/>report graded faithfulness scores rather than a<BR/>simple faithful/unfaithful label.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "10328909.c2" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">10328909.c2</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Multi-task loss for joint objectness<BR/>classification and bounding-box regression</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Faster R-CNN: Towards Real-Time Object Detection<BR/>with Region Proposal Networks</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper defines a unified loss function for<BR/>training Region Proposal Networks that<BR/>simultaneously optimizes a binary softmax<BR/>classification loss (object vs. background) and a<BR/>smooth‑L1 regression loss for bounding‑box<BR/>offsets. Positive anchors are defined by IoU &gt; 0.7<BR/>(or highest overlap) and the regression term is<BR/>activated only for these anchors; the two terms<BR/>are balanced by a weighting factor λ = 10. This<BR/>multi‑task loss enables end‑to‑end learning of<BR/>high‑quality, class‑agnostic proposals in a single<BR/>training pass.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "10328909.c7" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">10328909.c7</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Analysis of proposal recall versus detection mAP</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Faster R-CNN: Towards Real-Time Object Detection<BR/>with Region Proposal Networks</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper empirically evaluates how the<BR/>recall‑to‑IoU curves of three region proposal<BR/>methods (RPN, Selective Search, EdgeBoxes) relate<BR/>to the final object detection mean Average<BR/>Precision (mAP) obtained with Fast R‑CNN. By<BR/>measuring recall at multiple IoU thresholds and<BR/>comparing these curves to detection mAP, the<BR/>authors demonstrate that very high IoU recall<BR/>(&gt;0.8) is not necessary for strong detection<BR/>performance, explaining why the RPN maintains<BR/>accuracy with only 300 proposals.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "201103729.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">201103729.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">LXMERT multi‑encoder cross‑modality architecture</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">LXMERT: Learning Cross-Modality Encoder<BR/>Representations from Transformers</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces LXMERT, a Transformer‑based<BR/>vision‑and‑language model that separates<BR/>processing into three encoders: (1) an<BR/>object‑relationship encoder that consumes a<BR/>sequence of region‑of‑interest (RoI) visual<BR/>features, (2) a language encoder that processes<BR/>WordPiece‑tokenized sentences, and (3) a<BR/>cross‑modality encoder that repeatedly applies<BR/>bi‑directional cross‑attention followed by<BR/>self‑attention to fuse visual and textual streams.<BR/>The architecture also defines position‑aware<BR/>object embeddings that combine projected RoI<BR/>features with learned bounding‑box embeddings,<BR/>enabling joint reasoning over visual concepts and<BR/>linguistic semantics.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "211003735.c3" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">211003735.c3</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">BREAK Dataset of 83,978 Question–QDMR Pairs</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Break It Down: A Question Understanding Benchmark</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors construct BREAK, a large‑scale dataset<BR/>comprising 83,978 natural‑language questions<BR/>sampled from ten existing QA benchmarks across<BR/>three modalities (structured databases, text<BR/>passages, and images) together with high‑quality<BR/>Question Decomposition Meaning Representations<BR/>(QDMRs) annotated via crowdsourcing. The dataset<BR/>is split into train, development, and test sets<BR/>that respect original context boundaries, and is<BR/>released publicly along with the annotation<BR/>interface, validation tools, and code. BREAK<BR/>serves both as a resource for training QDMR<BR/>parsers and as a benchmark for evaluating<BR/>downstream multi‑hop QA and semantic parsing<BR/>systems.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "229371222.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">229371222.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">All‑At‑Once proof generation baseline for<BR/>natural‑language reasoning</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">ProofWriter: Generating Implications, Proofs, and<BR/>Abductive Statements over Natural Language</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces a single‑pass generative<BR/>baseline that fine‑tunes a pretrained T5<BR/>text‑to‑text model to map a natural‑language<BR/>theory and a query directly to an answer<BR/>(True/False/Unknown) together with a full<BR/>linearized proof and all intermediate conclusions.<BR/>The model is trained on the same data as the<BR/>iterative ProofWriter system but learns to emit<BR/>the entire proof in one generation step, enabling<BR/>direct comparison of proof quality, faithfulness,<BR/>and depth generalisation. The authors also propose<BR/>a verification procedure that re‑queries the same<BR/>model in QA mode for each intermediate step of the<BR/>generated proof to assess whether the proof<BR/>fragments are actually supported by the model.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#fde0c5"];
    "221535103.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">221535103.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">GPT‑f automated prover and proof assistant for<BR/>Metamath</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Generative Language Modeling for Automated Theorem<BR/>Proving</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces GPT‑f, a system that couples<BR/>a decoder‑only Transformer (up to 774 M<BR/>parameters) with a custom Python Metamath<BR/>verifier. GPT‑f generates a proof‑step (theorem<BR/>identifier and substitution list) conditioned on a<BR/>Metamath goal, expands open goals by sampling<BR/>multiple tactics, and orders them by cumulative<BR/>log‑probability in a breadth‑first proof search.<BR/>The system also supports an interactive<BR/>proof‑assistant mode and an iterative self‑play<BR/>loop that trains a provability value function on<BR/>generated proof data, achieving state‑of‑the‑art<BR/>performance on the Metamath set.mm benchmark.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#fde0c5"];
    "19449905.c5" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">19449905.c5</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Value‑network augmentation for MCTS using<BR/>apprentice estimates</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Thinking Fast and Slow with Deep Learning and Tree<BR/>Search</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces a multitask convolutional<BR/>neural network that jointly predicts a policy<BR/>distribution and a state‑value estimate for Hex<BR/>positions. The value target is obtained from<BR/>Monte‑Carlo rollouts of the current apprentice<BR/>policy, avoiding costly expert rollouts. During<BR/>tree search the learned value network replaces the<BR/>rollout component of Monte‑Carlo Tree Search,<BR/>providing fast value estimates that improve search<BR/>efficiency and increase playing strength.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "221535103.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">221535103.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Proof‑step conditional language‑modeling objective<BR/>(GOAL → PROOFSTEP)</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Generative Language Modeling for Automated Theorem<BR/>Proving</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper defines a training objective that treats<BR/>each Metamath proof step as a conditional<BR/>language‑modeling problem: given a serialized goal<BR/>token sequence, a decoder‑only Transformer<BR/>autoregressively generates the full proof‑step<BR/>(theorem identifier and substitution list) that<BR/>resolves the goal. The objective is implemented as<BR/>a token‑level cross‑entropy loss on the<BR/>concatenated string &quot;GOAL PROOFSTEP &quot;. This<BR/>enables end‑to‑end learning of proof generation<BR/>without separate premise‑selection or substitution<BR/>modules and integrates directly with a standard<BR/>Transformer architecture.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#fde0c5"];
    "211132980.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">211132980.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">MetaGen: Neural forward‑generation system for<BR/>Metamath theorems and proofs</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Learning to Prove Theorems by Learning to Generate<BR/>Theorems</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">MetaGen is a neural generator that synthesizes new<BR/>Metamath theorems together with full proof trees<BR/>by performing forward reasoning over existing<BR/>theorems. It selects an invocable background<BR/>theorem, constructs a substitution using a<BR/>relevance network and a substitution network, and<BR/>optionally grafts existing proof subtrees to<BR/>obtain multi‑step proofs. The system enforces<BR/>constraints that prevent meaningless theorems<BR/>(e.g., hypotheses must be existing expressions)<BR/>and restricts invoked theorems to those that<BR/>appear as background facts in the training tasks,<BR/>thereby producing synthetic data that are useful<BR/>for training theorem provers.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#fde0c5"];
    "8242113.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">8242113.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Systematic comparison of neural architectures for<BR/>embedding mathematical statements</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">DeepMath - Deep Sequence Models for Premise<BR/>Selection</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors evaluate three families of neural<BR/>networks—pure convolutional networks, pure<BR/>recurrent LSTM/GRU networks, and hybrid<BR/>recurrent‑convolutional models—for encoding<BR/>variable‑length first‑order logic strings<BR/>extracted from the Mizar Mathematical Library.<BR/>Each architecture is trained on premise‑selection<BR/>data and its ability to rank relevant axioms for<BR/>new conjectures is measured. Results show that<BR/>shallow CNNs with max‑pooling consistently<BR/>outperform deeper recurrent models on this task,<BR/>providing the first large‑scale empirical analysis<BR/>of sequence‑model designs for formal mathematical<BR/>language.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "3922816.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">3922816.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">ARC Dataset: large‑scale grade‑school science QA<BR/>benchmark with Challenge/Easy split</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Think you have Solved Question Answering? Try ARC,<BR/>the AI2 Reasoning Challenge</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces the AI2 Reasoning Challenge<BR/>(ARC) dataset, a collection of 7,787<BR/>natural‑language multiple‑choice science questions<BR/>drawn from real standardized tests for grades 3‑9.<BR/>The questions are partitioned into an Easy Set<BR/>(5,197 items) and a Challenge Set (2,590 items)<BR/>based on whether two simple baseline solvers—an<BR/>information‑retrieval (IR) system and a<BR/>pointwise‑mutual‑information (PMI) co‑occurrence<BR/>system—answer them correctly. This split creates a<BR/>benchmark that isolates questions requiring deeper<BR/>reasoning and knowledge integration, providing a<BR/>new problem formulation for evaluating advanced QA<BR/>systems.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#fde0c5"];
    "11816014.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">11816014.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Release of the Stanford Question Answering Dataset<BR/>(SQuAD) v1.0</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">SQuAD: 100,000+ Questions for Machine<BR/>Comprehension of Text</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces SQuAD, a large-scale<BR/>reading‑comprehension benchmark comprising 107,785<BR/>crowd‑generated question–answer pairs over 536<BR/>Wikipedia articles. Each answer is a contiguous<BR/>text span from the passage, enabling<BR/>span‑selection evaluation rather than<BR/>multiple‑choice. The dataset is split into<BR/>training, development, and test sets and is freely<BR/>released for unrestricted research use, providing<BR/>both a resource dataset and a standardized<BR/>benchmark for machine reading comprehension.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "2100831.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">2100831.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">MCTest MC160 and MC500 Reading‑Comprehension<BR/>Datasets with Standard Splits and Rich Metadata</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">MCTest: A Challenge Dataset for the Open-Domain<BR/>Machine Comprehension of Text</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors construct and publicly release two<BR/>non‑copyrighted corpora, MC160 (160 story sets)<BR/>and MC500 (500 story sets), each consisting of a<BR/>150‑300 word fictional story, four multiple‑choice<BR/>questions with four answer options, correct answer<BR/>labels, and extensive metadata<BR/>(age‑appropriateness, grammar quality, clarity,<BR/>and a flag indicating whether a question requires<BR/>information from multiple sentences). The corpora<BR/>are accompanied by predefined train/dev/test<BR/>splits, enabling immediate benchmarking of<BR/>machine‑reading systems. By providing both the raw<BR/>data and the evaluation protocol, the resource<BR/>serves as a benchmark for open‑domain machine<BR/>comprehension research.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "6203757.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">6203757.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Large-scale supervised reading-comprehension<BR/>dataset (CNN/Daily Mail)</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Teaching Machines to Read and Comprehend</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors construct a corpus of roughly one<BR/>million (context, query, answer) triples by<BR/>harvesting news articles from CNN and the Daily<BR/>Mail together with their abstractive bullet‑point<BR/>summaries. Each bullet point is turned into a<BR/>Cloze‑style question by replacing a single entity<BR/>with a placeholder, after which all entities are<BR/>anonymised and randomly permuted. This yields a<BR/>realistic, large‑scale supervised resource for<BR/>training and evaluating machine‑reading models,<BR/>and formalises reading comprehension as the<BR/>conditional probability p(a | c,q).</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "6203757.c2" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">6203757.c2</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">CNN/Daily Mail reading‑comprehension benchmark</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Teaching Machines to Read and Comprehend</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors define a standardized benchmark for<BR/>machine reading comprehension built on the CNN and<BR/>Daily Mail corpora. They publish fixed<BR/>train/validation/test splits, an evaluation<BR/>protocol that measures answer accuracy (p(a|c,q)),<BR/>and a suite of baseline results (majority,<BR/>frame‑semantic, word‑distance, Deep LSTM,<BR/>Attentive Reader, Impatient Reader). The benchmark<BR/>enforces document‑only reasoning by anonymising<BR/>and randomly permuting entity markers, thereby<BR/>eliminating world‑knowledge shortcuts.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "14915449.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">14915449.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Children&#x27;s Book Test (CBT) benchmark dataset</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">The Goldilocks Principle: Reading Children&#x27;s Books<BR/>with Explicit Memory Representations</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces the Children’s Book Test, a<BR/>large‑scale benchmark built from freely available<BR/>children’s books on Project Gutenberg. Each<BR/>example consists of a 20‑sentence context and a<BR/>21st query sentence with one word removed; the<BR/>model must select the correct word from ten<BR/>candidate answers drawn from the context. The<BR/>benchmark is split into four word‑type<BR/>categories—named entities, common nouns, verbs,<BR/>and prepositions—to explicitly assess a model’s<BR/>ability to exploit wider discourse context for<BR/>semantically rich words, and provides public<BR/>training, validation, and test splits.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "11816014.c4" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">11816014.c4</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Logistic regression model with lexicalized and<BR/>dependency‑tree path features for span selection<BR/>on SQuAD</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">SQuAD: 100,000+ Questions for Machine<BR/>Comprehension of Text</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors implement a feature‑based logistic<BR/>regression classifier to select answer spans in<BR/>the SQuAD reading‑comprehension task. The model<BR/>combines TF‑IDF word and bigram match scores,<BR/>root‑match indicators, span length and position<BR/>features, constituent label and POS‑tag features,<BR/>lexicalized word‑pair features, and<BR/>dependency‑tree path features extracted from<BR/>Stanford CoreNLP parses. Trained with AdaGrad and<BR/>L2 regularization, it attains 51.0 % F1 on the<BR/>SQuAD test set, substantially outperforming a<BR/>sliding‑window baseline, and an ablation study<BR/>shows that lexicalized and dependency‑path<BR/>features contribute the most to performance.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "26501419.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">26501419.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">TriviaQA large‑scale reading‑comprehension dataset<BR/>with distant supervision</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">TriviaQA: A Large Scale Distantly Supervised<BR/>Challenge Dataset for Reading Comprehension</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper releases TriviaQA, a publicly available<BR/>reading‑comprehension resource comprising over 650<BR/>K (question, answer, evidence‑document) triples.<BR/>Questions are authored by trivia enthusiasts<BR/>independent of any evidence, and evidence<BR/>documents are collected retrospectively from<BR/>Wikipedia and Web search results (average ≈6<BR/>documents per question). The release includes a<BR/>noisy automatically gathered portion, a clean<BR/>human‑verified subset of 1 975 triples, code for<BR/>data collection and preprocessing, baseline<BR/>experiments, and standard training, development,<BR/>and test splits for benchmarking RC models.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "11816014.c5-1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">11816014.c5-1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Exact Match and token‑level F1 evaluation metrics<BR/>for span‑based QA</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">SQuAD: 100,000+ Questions for Machine<BR/>Comprehension of Text</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper defines two token‑level evaluation<BR/>metrics for the SQuAD reading‑comprehension task.<BR/>Exact Match (EM) requires the predicted answer<BR/>span to match any ground‑truth span exactly, while<BR/>the token‑level F1 score measures the harmonic<BR/>mean of token precision and recall, ignoring<BR/>punctuation and articles. These metrics provide a<BR/>reproducible, fine‑grained benchmark for comparing<BR/>machine reading models on span selection.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "26501419.c3-3" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">26501419.c3-3</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Modified BiDAF architecture for long,<BR/>multi-document evidence</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">TriviaQA: A Large Scale Distantly Supervised<BR/>Challenge Dataset for Reading Comprehension</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper adapts the Bidirectional Attention Flow<BR/>(BiDAF) neural reading‑comprehension model to the<BR/>TriviaQA setting by (i) truncating each evidence<BR/>document to the first 800 tokens so that the model<BR/>can process long web and Wikipedia articles, (ii)<BR/>applying the model independently to each document<BR/>in the evidence set, and (iii) aggregating the<BR/>per‑document answer confidence scores via<BR/>summation to produce a final answer prediction.<BR/>This enables a state‑of‑the‑art RC architecture to<BR/>handle the noisy, multi‑document inputs<BR/>characteristic of TriviaQA.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "8535316.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">8535316.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Hierarchical multi‑stage embedding pipeline</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Bidirectional Attention Flow for Machine<BR/>Comprehension</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces a three‑level embedding<BR/>hierarchy applied to both context and query<BR/>tokens. First, each word is encoded with a<BR/>character‑level embedding obtained via a 1‑D<BR/>convolutional neural network (CNN) followed by<BR/>max‑pooling, capturing sub‑word morphology.<BR/>Second, a pretrained GloVe word vector is<BR/>concatenated to the character embedding, providing<BR/>lexical semantics. Third, the concatenated vectors<BR/>are processed by a two‑layer Highway network and a<BR/>bidirectional LSTM to produce contextual<BR/>embeddings that encode surrounding word<BR/>information before any attention is applied. This<BR/>pipeline yields rich token‑level features that<BR/>combine morphology, semantics, and context.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "8535316.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">8535316.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Bidirectional attention flow layer with<BR/>memory‑less static attention</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Bidirectional Attention Flow for Machine<BR/>Comprehension</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The BiDAF model introduces an attention‑flow layer<BR/>that computes a similarity matrix S between every<BR/>context token and every query token using a<BR/>trainable scalar function α that combines<BR/>concatenated vectors, element‑wise products and<BR/>linear terms. From S it derives two complementary<BR/>attentions: (i) context‑to‑query (C2Q) attention,<BR/>producing a query‑aware vector for each context<BR/>word via a softmax over the query dimension, and<BR/>(ii) query‑to‑context (Q2C) attention, extracting<BR/>a single context vector by taking the max over the<BR/>context dimension followed by a softmax. The<BR/>attentions are memory‑less: each attention weight<BR/>depends only on the current context word and the<BR/>full query, allowing the attention vectors to be<BR/>pre‑computed and passed unchanged to a subsequent<BR/>modeling Bi‑LSTM, avoiding early summarization of<BR/>the context.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "8535316.c2" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">8535316.c2</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Task‑specific output head for QA formats</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Bidirectional Attention Flow for Machine<BR/>Comprehension</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">BiDAF defines a modular output layer that is<BR/>decoupled from the shared encoder. For the SQuAD<BR/>span‑selection task the head consists of two<BR/>independent linear classifiers that produce<BR/>softmax distributions over start and end token<BR/>positions, followed by a joint maximisation to<BR/>select the answer span. For cloze‑style<BR/>reading‑comprehension tasks the head predicts only<BR/>a start index and applies a mask that restricts<BR/>scoring to anonymised entity tokens. This design<BR/>enables the same BiDAF encoder to be reused across<BR/>different machine‑comprehension formulations with<BR/>minimal changes.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "26501419.c5" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">26501419.c5</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Human‑verified clean evaluation subset of TriviaQA</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">TriviaQA: A Large Scale Distantly Supervised<BR/>Challenge Dataset for Reading Comprehension</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors construct a high‑quality subset of<BR/>1,975 question‑document‑answer triples drawn from<BR/>the larger TriviaQA collection. Each triple is<BR/>manually verified: annotators confirm that the<BR/>evidence document contains all facts required to<BR/>answer the question, eliminating noise and<BR/>missing‑evidence issues present in the<BR/>automatically gathered data. This verified subset<BR/>is released alongside the full dataset and code,<BR/>providing a reliable benchmark for measuring true<BR/>reading‑comprehension performance.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "8495258.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">8495258.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Decomposable Attention Model for Natural Language<BR/>Inference</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">A Decomposable Attention Model for Natural<BR/>Language Inference</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces a neural architecture for the<BR/>natural language inference (NLI) task that<BR/>replaces recurrent or convolutional encoders with<BR/>a three‑stage pipeline: (1) Attend – a soft,<BR/>dot‑product attention that aligns each word in the<BR/>premise with a weighted combination of words in<BR/>the hypothesis; (2) Compare – a feed‑forward<BR/>network that jointly processes each aligned word<BR/>pair; (3) Aggregate – sum‑pooling of the<BR/>comparison vectors followed by a final<BR/>feed‑forward classifier. The model operates<BR/>directly on fixed word‑embedding vectors, does not<BR/>rely on explicit word‑order information, and is<BR/>fully parallelizable across token positions,<BR/>achieving state‑of‑the‑art accuracy on SNLI with<BR/>far fewer parameters than LSTM‑based baselines.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "8495258.c2" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">8495258.c2</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">State‑of‑the‑Art Empirical Evaluation on SNLI with<BR/>Parameter‑Efficient Decomposable Attention Models</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">A Decomposable Attention Model for Natural<BR/>Language Inference</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors train the vanilla Decomposable<BR/>Attention (DA) model and its<BR/>intra‑sentence‑attention variant on the Stanford<BR/>Natural Language Inference (SNLI) corpus,<BR/>achieving 86.3% test accuracy with 382 K<BR/>parameters and 86.8% with 582 K parameters<BR/>respectively. These results surpass previously<BR/>reported LSTM, CNN, and tree‑based NLI systems<BR/>while using roughly an order of magnitude fewer<BR/>trainable parameters. The paper also provides a<BR/>per‑class accuracy breakdown and a qualitative<BR/>error analysis illustrating the strengths and<BR/>limitations of the approach.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "2135897.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">2135897.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Conditional Encoding LSTM Architecture for RTE</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Reasoning about Entailment with Neural Attention</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces a recurrent architecture for<BR/>Recognizing Textual Entailment (RTE) in which the<BR/>premise sentence is first processed by an LSTM;<BR/>the final cell state of this LSTM is then used to<BR/>initialise a second LSTM that reads the<BR/>hypothesis. By conditioning the hypothesis<BR/>encoding on the premise representation, the model<BR/>allows information to flow directly between the<BR/>two sentences, avoiding independent encoding of<BR/>each sentence. This design yields a<BR/>3.3‑percentage‑point accuracy improvement over the<BR/>independent‑encoding baseline on the Stanford<BR/>Natural Language Inference (SNLI) corpus.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "6506243.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">6506243.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Long Short-Term Memory-Network (LSTMN)<BR/>architecture</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Long Short-Term Memory-Networks for Machine<BR/>Reading</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper proposes the Long Short-Term<BR/>Memory-Network (LSTMN), a recurrent neural network<BR/>that replaces the single memory cell of a standard<BR/>LSTM with an internal memory network composed of<BR/>multiple slots, each storing the contextual<BR/>representation of a token. The model maintains a<BR/>hidden-state tape for interaction with the<BR/>environment and a memory tape that grows with the<BR/>sequence length up to a predefined span, enabling<BR/>non-Markovian state updates. An intra-attention<BR/>mechanism softly addresses the memory slots at<BR/>each time step, allowing adaptive memory usage,<BR/>incremental left-to-right processing, and weak<BR/>induction of undirected lexical relations, thereby<BR/>mitigating the memory-compression and structural<BR/>limitations of vanilla LSTMs.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "6506243.c3-3" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">6506243.c3-3</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Empirical evaluation of LSTMN with<BR/>attention-fusion on SNLI natural language<BR/>inference</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Long Short-Term Memory-Networks for Machine<BR/>Reading</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors integrate the Long Short-Term<BR/>Memory-Network (LSTMN) into an encoder-decoder<BR/>framework using shallow and deep attention-fusion<BR/>strategies and evaluate the resulting models on<BR/>the Stanford Natural Language Inference (SNLI)<BR/>corpus. The shallow-fusion LSTMN and the<BR/>deep-fusion LSTMN (300‑dimensional hidden units)<BR/>achieve test accuracies of 84.3% and 86.3%<BR/>respectively, matching or surpassing prior<BR/>state‑of‑the‑art results while using a comparable<BR/>number of parameters. This demonstrates that<BR/>combining intra‑attention, inter‑sentence<BR/>attention, and a memory‑network‑augmented<BR/>recurrence effectively models sentence‑pair<BR/>semantics for natural language inference.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "2926851.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">2926851.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Memory Networks conceptual framework</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Memory Networks</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces a general class of learning<BR/>models called Memory Networks that combine a<BR/>long‑term external memory with standard inference<BR/>components. The architecture is defined by four<BR/>modular functions: I (input mapping), G (memory<BR/>update), O (output generation by retrieving<BR/>supporting memories), and R (response generation).<BR/>This high‑level framework is algorithm‑agnostic,<BR/>allowing any learning method to be used for each<BR/>module and enabling read/write access to a<BR/>scalable memory for tasks such as question<BR/>answering.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "2926851.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">2926851.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Memory Neural Network (MemNN) architecture for<BR/>textual QA</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Memory Networks</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper presents a concrete neural<BR/>implementation of the Memory Networks framework<BR/>for question answering over text. Sentences (facts<BR/>or questions) are stored verbatim in a growing<BR/>memory array via the I and G modules. At inference<BR/>time the O module retrieves up to k supporting<BR/>memories using learned embedding similarity<BR/>scores, and the R module produces a single‑word<BR/>answer by scoring candidate answer words with a<BR/>separate embedding matrix. The implementation uses<BR/>bag‑of‑words feature mappings, distinct embedding<BR/>matrices for retrieval and answer scoring, and is<BR/>trained with a margin ranking loss optimized by<BR/>stochastic gradient descent.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "868693.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">868693.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Co‑Attention Mechanism for Joint Image‑Question<BR/>Reasoning</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Hierarchical Question-Image Co-Attention for<BR/>Visual Question Answering</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces a co‑attention framework that<BR/>simultaneously computes attention distributions<BR/>over image regions and over question tokens,<BR/>allowing the two modalities to guide each other.<BR/>An affinity matrix is built between image feature<BR/>vectors and hierarchical question representations,<BR/>and attention weights are learned from this<BR/>matrix. Two concrete strategies are defined: (a)<BR/>parallel co‑attention, which generates image and<BR/>question attentions in a single step, and (b)<BR/>alternating co‑attention, which iteratively<BR/>refines one modality’s attention conditioned on<BR/>the other’s summary. This symmetric design enables<BR/>richer cross‑modal interaction than prior<BR/>visual‑only attention models.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "6203757.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">6203757.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Entity anonymisation and permutation pipeline</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Teaching Machines to Read and Comprehend</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces a preprocessing pipeline for<BR/>the reading‑comprehension dataset that (a) runs a<BR/>coreference resolver to group mentions of the same<BR/>real‑world entity, (b) replaces each entity with<BR/>an abstract marker such as ent23, and (c) randomly<BR/>permutes these markers each time a data point is<BR/>loaded. This removes any reliance on<BR/>world‑knowledge cues and forces models to answer<BR/>questions solely from the provided document<BR/>context.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "8535316.c3-1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">8535316.c3-1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">State‑of‑the‑art performance on SQuAD benchmark</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Bidirectional Attention Flow for Machine<BR/>Comprehension</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The BiDAF model attains the highest reported Exact<BR/>Match (73.3 %) and F1 (81.1 %) scores on the<BR/>hidden test set of the Stanford Question Answering<BR/>Dataset (SQuAD) at the time of submission, using<BR/>an ensemble of 12 independently trained runs. This<BR/>result demonstrates that the proposed<BR/>architecture, which combines hierarchical<BR/>embeddings, memory‑less bidirectional attention<BR/>flow, and a span‑selection output head,<BR/>outperforms all previously published systems on<BR/>this large‑scale reading‑comprehension benchmark.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "8535316.c3-2" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">8535316.c3-2</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">State‑of‑the‑art performance on CNN/DailyMail<BR/>cloze test</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Bidirectional Attention Flow for Machine<BR/>Comprehension</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">Using a slight modification of the output layer,<BR/>BiDAF achieves the highest reported accuracy on<BR/>the CNN and DailyMail cloze‑style<BR/>reading‑comprehension datasets for both single‑run<BR/>and 12‑model ensemble configurations, surpassing<BR/>prior memory‑network and attention‑based<BR/>approaches. This demonstrates the model’s ability<BR/>to generalize from span‑selection to<BR/>entity‑prediction tasks. The experiments reuse the<BR/>same BiDAF encoder as for SQuAD, are trained with<BR/>AdaDelta and dropout on a single GPU, and evaluate<BR/>on the standard CNN/DailyMail benchmark.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "218974301.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">218974301.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">WorldTree V2 multi‑fact explanation dataset</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">WorldTree V2: A Corpus of Science-Domain<BR/>Structured Explanations and Inference Patterns<BR/>supporting Multi-Hop Inference</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors release WorldTree V2, a corpus of<BR/>5,114 standardized elementary and middle‑school<BR/>science multiple‑choice questions each paired with<BR/>a detailed, human‑authored explanation graph that<BR/>combines on average six atomic facts. Explanations<BR/>are represented as lexically‑connected graphs<BR/>drawn from a manually curated semi‑structured<BR/>knowledge base of 9,216 facts across 66 tables.<BR/>This resource triples the size of the original<BR/>WorldTree corpus and covers roughly half of all<BR/>publicly available U.S. science exam questions,<BR/>providing training and evaluation data for<BR/>many‑fact multi‑hop inference.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#fde0c5"];
    "199668863.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">199668863.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Hierarchical taxonomy of 406 fine-grained problem<BR/>domains for K‑12 science exams</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Multi-class Hierarchical Question Classification<BR/>for Multiple Choice Science Exams</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors construct a six‑level hierarchical<BR/>taxonomy covering 406 detailed problem domains<BR/>(e.g., Astronomy → Gravitational Pull, Life<BR/>Science → Photosynthesis). The taxonomy is derived<BR/>from the NY Regents exam syllabus, three publicly<BR/>available science study guides, and the 7,787<BR/>multiple‑choice questions in the ARC corpus. Each<BR/>node is accompanied by a concise textual<BR/>definition, enabling categorization of questions<BR/>at multiple granularities for downstream<BR/>question‑classification and QA systems.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "11039301.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">11039301.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Two‑Layered Semantic Taxonomy of Answer Types</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Learning Question Classifiers</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper defines a two‑level taxonomy for answer<BR/>types used in open‑domain question answering. Six<BR/>coarse categories (ABBREVIATION, ENTITY,<BR/>DESCRIPTION, HUMAN, LOCATION, NUMERIC VALUE) are<BR/>introduced to align with existing entity<BR/>recognizers and to provide a manageable top‑level<BR/>partition. Each coarse class is further refined<BR/>into 50 mutually exclusive fine‑grained subclasses<BR/>(e.g., city, speed, definition) based on analysis<BR/>of the TREC‑10 question set, yielding a natural<BR/>semantic hierarchy that serves as the label space<BR/>for a hierarchical classifier and guides<BR/>downstream answer‑selection strategies.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "5421278.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">5421278.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Comprehensive exposition of Cohen&#x27;s kappa<BR/>statistic</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Interrater reliability: the kappa statistic</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper presents a detailed exposition of<BR/>Cohen&#x27;s kappa, the chance‑adjusted interrater<BR/>reliability coefficient for two raters. It derives<BR/>the full mathematical formulation, defining<BR/>observed agreement Pr(a) and expected agreement<BR/>Pr(e) from marginal totals of a 2×2 contingency<BR/>table, and shows step‑by‑step computation. The<BR/>exposition also recounts Jacob Cohen’s original<BR/>1960s development of the statistic and restates<BR/>the conventional qualitative interpretation scale<BR/>(≤0 no agreement, 0.01‑0.20 slight, …, 0.81‑1.00<BR/>almost perfect).</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "5421278.c4" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">5421278.c4</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Guideline to report both percent agreement and<BR/>Cohen&#x27;s kappa based on expected guessing</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Interrater reliability: the kappa statistic</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors recommend that researchers calculate<BR/>and present both the simple percent agreement<BR/>statistic and Cohen&#x27;s kappa when evaluating<BR/>interrater reliability. They advise using percent<BR/>agreement when raters are well‑trained and random<BR/>guessing is unlikely, and using kappa when<BR/>substantial guessing is suspected, thereby<BR/>providing a practical decision rule that balances<BR/>interpretability with adjustment for chance<BR/>agreement.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "199668863.c1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">199668863.c1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Annotated ARC question‑classification dataset<BR/>(7,787 questions)</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Multi-class Hierarchical Question Classification<BR/>for Multiple Choice Science Exams</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors release a publicly available dataset<BR/>that augments the 7,787 multiple‑choice science<BR/>questions from the ARC corpus with up to two<BR/>hierarchical labels drawn from a 406‑category<BR/>taxonomy. Each question was independently labeled<BR/>by two expert annotators, disagreements were<BR/>resolved, and the final labels achieve an<BR/>estimated 96 % accuracy (Cohen&#x27;s κ = 0.58 at the<BR/>finest level). The release includes the full<BR/>taxonomy, label definitions, and serves both as a<BR/>resource and a benchmark for hierarchical,<BR/>multi‑label question classification.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "5421278.c2-1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">5421278.c2-1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Revised minimum Cohen&#x27;s kappa threshold for<BR/>acceptable interrater reliability in health<BR/>research</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Interrater reliability: the kappa statistic</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors propose that health‑related studies<BR/>should require a Cohen&#x27;s kappa of at least 0.80 to<BR/>be considered acceptable, arguing that the<BR/>traditional &quot;moderate&quot; band (0.40–0.60) can<BR/>conceal 40–50 % erroneous data. A new<BR/>interpretation table is presented that<BR/>reclassifies kappa values below 0.80 as<BR/>insufficient for clinical decision‑making.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "5421278.c3" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">5421278.c3</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Guidelines for 95% confidence interval computation<BR/>for Cohen&#x27;s kappa and recommended minimum sample<BR/>sizes</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Interrater reliability: the kappa statistic</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper provides a practical procedure for<BR/>constructing a 95 % confidence interval around a<BR/>Cohen’s κ estimate using the normal‑approximation<BR/>formula κ ± 1.96·SE(κ). It explains how the<BR/>standard error of κ depends on the number of<BR/>paired ratings and demonstrates that small samples<BR/>yield wide intervals. Based on this relationship,<BR/>the authors recommend a minimum of 30 paired<BR/>observations to achieve a reasonably narrow<BR/>interval and suggest that samples of 1 000 or more<BR/>produce very precise estimates. These guidelines<BR/>link sample‑size planning directly to the<BR/>reliability assessment of κ in health‑research<BR/>contexts.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "5421278.c6-1" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">5421278.c6-1</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Critical analysis of the rater independence<BR/>assumption underlying Cohen&#x27;s kappa</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Interrater reliability: the kappa statistic</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper argues that the assumption of<BR/>statistical independence between raters, which<BR/>underlies the derivation of Cohen&#x27;s kappa, is<BR/>frequently violated in health‑care rating tasks<BR/>because raters may be trained together, share<BR/>protocols, or otherwise influence each other&#x27;s<BR/>judgments, leading to biased kappa estimates.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "5421278.c6-2" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">5421278.c6-2</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Critical analysis of the marginal‑total<BR/>chance‑agreement assumption in Cohen&#x27;s kappa</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Interrater reliability: the kappa statistic</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper critiques the use of marginal totals of<BR/>the rating matrix to estimate chance agreement,<BR/>noting that this estimate presumes raters behave<BR/>as independent random draws from the marginal<BR/>distribution—a condition that may be violated when<BR/>categories are unequally prevalent or when raters<BR/>share systematic biases.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "5421278.c6-3" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">5421278.c6-3</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Critical analysis of the guessing‑behavior<BR/>assumption in Cohen&#x27;s kappa</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Interrater reliability: the kappa statistic</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper examines the assumption that when raters<BR/>guess, the probability of each possible rating<BR/>equals the marginal proportion of that rating in<BR/>the data, arguing that real‑world guessing may<BR/>follow different patterns, which can cause the<BR/>kappa adjustment for chance to be inaccurate.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "3623373.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">3623373.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">WorldTree explanation graph corpus</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">WorldTree: A Corpus of Explanation Graphs for<BR/>Elementary Science Questions supporting Multi-Hop<BR/>Inference</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces WorldTree, an open‑source<BR/>dataset comprising 1,680 elementary‑science<BR/>multiple‑choice questions (grades 3‑5) each paired<BR/>with a multi‑sentence explanation graph.<BR/>Explanations are provided both as free‑text<BR/>sentences and as a lexically‑overlapping graph of<BR/>table rows, with each sentence assigned one of<BR/>four roles (central, grounding, background,<BR/>lexical glue). The resource also includes the<BR/>underlying semi‑structured tablestore and the<BR/>annotation tooling used to construct the corpus,<BR/>enabling training and evaluation of explainable<BR/>question‑answering systems.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "2498076.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">2498076.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Explanation‑centered analysis framework for<BR/>elementary science QA</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">What&#x27;s in an Explanation? Characterizing Knowledge<BR/>and Inference Requirements for Elementary Science<BR/>Exams</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper introduces a systematic framework that<BR/>constructs gold natural‑language explanations for<BR/>multiple‑choice elementary science questions by<BR/>retrieving grade‑appropriate sentences from study<BR/>guides, a science dictionary, and Simple English<BR/>Wiktionary, reusing sentences when possible and<BR/>inserting bridge sentences that explicitly link<BR/>concepts. These explanations are annotated with a<BR/>fine‑grained taxonomy of knowledge and inference<BR/>types and are used to characterize the knowledge<BR/>and inference requirements of each question,<BR/>enabling quantitative comparison of<BR/>retrieval‑based and inference‑based solvers and<BR/>informing future knowledge‑base construction and<BR/>solver design.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "2498076.c5" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">2498076.c5</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Analytical insights on knowledge distribution and<BR/>implications for QA system design</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">What&#x27;s in an Explanation? Characterizing Knowledge<BR/>and Inference Requirements for Elementary Science<BR/>Exams</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors analyze the fine‑grained knowledge and<BR/>inference requirements of 212 elementary science<BR/>questions, finding that roughly 77 % of them<BR/>require complex inference involving multiple<BR/>knowledge types. They then compare a<BR/>retrieval‑only learning‑to‑rank model with two<BR/>inference‑based solvers (TableILP and STITCH) on<BR/>the same dataset, showing that inference solvers<BR/>achieve higher overall accuracy and especially<BR/>improve performance on the complex‑inference<BR/>subset. From these observations they argue that<BR/>future QA systems should employ ensembles or<BR/>question‑specific solver selection and that the<BR/>fine‑grained taxonomy can guide the construction<BR/>of targeted knowledge bases.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "7145148.c4" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">7145148.c4</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Semi‑structured table corpus for<BR/>elementary‑science QA</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Question Answering via Integer Programming over<BR/>Semi-Structured Knowledge</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors construct a knowledge base comprising<BR/>65 manually or semi‑automatically built tables<BR/>(≈5,000 rows) whose schemas are derived from<BR/>elementary‑science curricula, together with four<BR/>Open‑IE tables (≈2,600 rows) extracted from<BR/>science texts. Each table is represented as an<BR/>n‑ary predicate over short natural‑language<BR/>phrases, providing a semi‑structured substrate for<BR/>the TableILP reasoning system. The corpus is<BR/>released publicly as a resource for QA research on<BR/>elementary‑science multiple‑choice questions.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#e3d5ff"];
    "3623373.c5" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">3623373.c5</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Guidelines for explanation depth and annotation<BR/>protocol</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">WorldTree: A Corpus of Explanation Graphs for<BR/>Elementary Science Questions supporting Multi-Hop<BR/>Inference</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper defines a set of design principles that<BR/>specify four levels of explanatory depth (young<BR/>child, domain novice, domain expert, first<BR/>principles) and couples these with a detailed<BR/>annotation protocol. The protocol includes<BR/>explicit sentence‑role labeling (central,<BR/>grounding, background, lexical glue), a multi‑pass<BR/>review process, and reuse strategies to ensure<BR/>that explanations are consistent, high‑quality,<BR/>and suitable for training explainable inference<BR/>models for elementary science QA.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "3623373.c3" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">3623373.c3</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Web‑based collaborative annotation tool for<BR/>constructing explanation graphs</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">WorldTree: A Corpus of Explanation Graphs for<BR/>Elementary Science Questions supporting Multi-Hop<BR/>Inference</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The authors built a web‑based collaborative<BR/>interface that enables annotators to author<BR/>explanation graphs for elementary science<BR/>questions. The tool provides keyword search over<BR/>the semi‑structured tablestore, re‑use of<BR/>previously authored explanations, visualisation of<BR/>lexical overlap between sentences, and flagging of<BR/>quality issues. Explanations are stored as ordered<BR/>lists of table‑row identifiers, allowing later<BR/>modifications to the underlying tables to<BR/>propagate automatically to all explanations. The<BR/>interface also implements a multi‑pass review<BR/>workflow with role‑labeling flags to enforce the<BR/>annotation protocol.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, fillcolor="#f9d5e5"];
    "233297051.c0" [label=<<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="10" COLOR="gray40">233297051.c0</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><B><FONT POINT-SIZE="14">Formulation of explanation as multistep entailment<BR/>trees</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><I><FONT POINT-SIZE="11" COLOR="gray25">Explaining Answers with Entailment Trees</FONT></I></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD><FONT POINT-SIZE="11">The paper reconceives open-domain textual<BR/>question-answering explanation as the construction<BR/>of a directed entailment tree, where each node is<BR/>a multi-premise textual entailment step that<BR/>incrementally derives the hypothesis (question +<BR/>answer) from known facts. This formulation<BR/>separates the correctness of the derivation from<BR/>its utility for users, enabling systematic<BR/>evaluation of explanations independent of answer<BR/>selection. By defining explanations as trees<BR/>rather than isolated rationales, the work provides<BR/>a high-level conceptual framework that can guide<BR/>future research on explainable QA.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>>, style="rounded,filled,bold", penwidth=2.5, fillcolor="#fff2b2"];
    "233297051.c0" -> "29033327.c0";
    "29033327.c0" -> "14604520.c0";
    "14604520.c0" -> "16404002.c0";
    "29033327.c0" -> "14604520.c1";
